<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AngolaSouthAfrica     05-14 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola South Africa,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Both Sides Say Second Round of Talks Made Progress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY ROBERT WELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRAZZAVILLE, Congo (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Both sides reported progress at the
second round of South Africa-Angola talks which ended Friday and
said the talks would lead to further meetings soon involving the
United States and Cuba.
   The governments are seeking an end to conflicts in southern
Africa that include a civil war in Marxist Angola and a war for
independence in South-West Africa, also known as Namibia.
   South Africa's foreign minister, Roelof Botha, said, ``I hope
that what we have started would one day be rewarded with peace,
stability and prosperity for the whole of southern Africa.
   ``We are both agreed that there can be no military solution for
our continent and in particular for southern Africa.''
   The South African delegation was exuberant and clearly
considered its reception in this socialist nation a triumph.
   Botha exchanged gifts with Foreign Minister Antoine Ndinga-Oba
of the Congo before leaving for home.
   Congolese sources said Botha met privately with President Denis
Sassou Nguesso, one of the continent's most vocal opponents of
apartheid, South Africa's policy of racial separation.
   The sources spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Justice Minister Fernando Van-Dunem led Angola's delegation.
   ``We do know what each other wants and we cleared our stance,''
he said.
   Angolan and South African officials said U.S. and Cuban
diplomats would attend the next session of talks. Both nations
attended talks last week in London aimed at a regional peace
settlement.
   The U.S. administration seeks withdrawal of an estimated 40,000
Cuban soldiers from Angola. Cuba says its forces are there to help
Angola fend off South African incursions. Rebels who have been
fighting a guerrilla war for 13 years, seeking to overthrow the
Angolan government, are supported by the United States.
   The South-West Africa People's Organization, or SWAPO, also is
fighting a bush war trying to force South Africa to leave
South-West Africa, commonly known as Namibia, and for Namibia to
become independent.
   Friday's four-hour talks were held in a small, government-owned
villa and ended on a cordial note with each side thanking the other
for its frankness.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
