<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MalpracticeAward     05-14 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Malpractice Award,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Awards $10 Million to Brain-Damaged Boy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury awarded $10 million Friday to a
Northern Virginia child who suffered irreversible brain damage
during birth.
   The four-man, two-woman U.S. District Court jury decided on the
award after hearing testimony that three doctors named in the case
did not act quickly when tests indicated the baby's heart rate was
slowing.
   Jack Olender, attorney for 3-year-old Edward Leahy, Jr., said he
believed it was the largest medical malpractice award ever in the
District of Columbia.
   Olender said obstetricians Richard Newman, Julian Safran, and
Stephen Horwitz performed an emergency caesarian section delivery
about four hours after problems were first noticed.
   The operation was not conducted in time to prevent the child
from suffering irreversible brain damage, Olender said.
   ``He's unable to walk, talk, or feed himself,'' said Olender.
``Everything has to be done for him.''
   The judgment is about $6 million dollars greater than the
malpractice insurance policy held by the doctors, who are in
partnership.
   The child's parents, Edward R. and Patricia Leahy of McLean,
Va., will receive no compensation in the award, Olender said.
Instead, the money will be placed in a trust fund under court
approval and used for the child's care.
   Attorneys for the doctors did not say whether an appeal of the
verdict or award is planned.
   Problems in the birth arose around 4 a.m. on Dec. 11, 1984, when
an electronic fetal monitor indicated that the child's heart rate
was slowing, Olender told the court.
   In such cases, a declining heart rate often indicates a shortage
of oxygen, usually resulting from a pinching of the umbilical cord,
and emergency caesarian section deliveries are usually performed as
soon as the problem is discovered, Olender asserted.
   The emergency operation did not take place until 9:15 a.m.
   Columbia Hospital for Women _ the Washington, D.C. hospital
where the birth took place _ originally was named in the suit, but
was dropped from the case when it agreed to pay $800,000 in a
settlement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
