<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Publisher-Holocaust     05-14 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Publisher-Holocaust,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Publisher Gets Nine-Month Sentence For Printing Statements Denying
Holocaust</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A publisher convicted in a retrial of maliciously
publishing statements denying the Holocaust was sentenced Friday to
nine months in jail.
   Ernst Zundel, 49, arrived at the district courthouse bearing a
small coffin inscribed with the words ``Free Speech is Dead.''
   After his 1985 conviction he went to his sentencing carring a
heavy wooden cross, also signifying the demise of freedom of speech
in Canada.
   As in his earlier conviction, Zundel is seeking to appeal his
sentence and jury conviction and has applied for bail to keep him
out of jail at least until his appeal can be considered. But he had
to start the weekend behind bars awaiting a bail decision.
   The West German immigrant won his first appeal and was granted a
new trial in district court that ended in the second conviction.
   Zundel, who operates Samisdat Publishers in Toronto, was charged
under a law forbidding publication of statements known to be false
or likely to cause injury or mischief to the public interest.
   Zundel was charged with publishing a booklet _ which he did not
write _ that denies official accounts of Nazis exterminating Jews
in wartime prison camps. The booklet says the horror stories about
the Holocaust were all a hoax and a fraudulent scheme by Zionists
to extract financial reparation from postwar Germany.
   However, Judge Ronald Thomas took judicial notice of the
Holocaust at the beginning of the trial, recognizing it as a
historical fact. From then on, Zundel's essential defense was that
he honestly believed the contents of the pamphlet and was not
knowingly spreading false news, as the charge alleged.
   Jewish leaders were happy with the verdict, saying it would
serve to protect ethnic minorities from social intolerance.
   The Canadian Jewish Congress said it ``demonstrates that
Canadians will not tolerate the vilification of ethnological
communities.
   ``It reaffirms the effectiveness of the Criminal Code in
upholding social and racial harmony,'' group officials said.
   B'nai B'rith Canada expressed confidence the outcome ``will
serve to deter hatemongers, no matter who their targets may be,
from pursuing their aim of dividing Canadian society and turning
some of us against our fellow citizens.''
</TEXT>
