<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDS-Education 1stLd-Writethru a0798 05-14 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Education, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0798,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CDC and Teachers Open Conference on AIDS Education</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to ADD NEA membership; PICKS UP 4th
graf pvs, `The role ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Centers for Disease Control and the National
Education Association launched their first joint conference on AIDS
and education Friday with a focus on showing teachers how to teach
about the deadly disease.
   The three-day conference, expected to draw 100 educators from
around the country, is the latest event in what NEA President Mary
Hatwood Futrell described as her association's ``all-out war
against AIDS.''
   ``We are going to work with our members to determine what we can
do as an organization to raise the consciousness level of the
members of our profession,'' said Ms. Futtrell.
   The NEA is the nation's largest teacher union, with 1.9 million
members.
   ``The role of a teacher is a especially critical in dealing with
young people,'' she said. ``Children trust their teachers and they
will go to their teachers for information. We must have factual
information and know how to respond to young people.''
   Ms. Futrell added she hopes the conference will spur action on
AIDS education.
   ``We don't think we can wait five years,'' she said. ``We need
to begin to talk to young people now about changing their behavior
so they don't get the disease.''
   Friday's keynote speaker was John W. Washburn Jr., an AIDS
patient who is retired superintendent of the Brighton School
District near Rochester, N.Y.
   ``We've got a mission,'' Washburn said in an interview before
his address. ``The kids in our high schools are going to bear the
brunt of this disease and they're going to bear the cost.''
   Washburn, 48, was diagnosed last spring with AIDS and disclosed
his illness in January, when he embarked on a series of appearances
and speeches to educate high school and college students and
teachers about the disease.
   ``Exploit me,'' said Washburn. ``My time is limited. I want to
be exploited by whoever can use me to put windows on what is now
happening with AIDS and what is likely to happen.
   ``My years in public school work have groomed me. ... I'm not
embarrassed by the questions,'' said Washburn, who is homosexual.
   Other participants in the conference include researchers and
officials of the Atlanta-based CDC. Discussion will include ways to
incorporate AIDS education into the school curriculum.
   The NEA and the CDC's parent agency, the U.S. Public Health
Service, are members of the Health Information Network, created in
1987 in an AIDS education effort. Last fall, the network
distributed 1.9 million copies of a handbook for teachers on AIDS.
   AIDS has struck 973 American children under age 13; of those,
566 have died, according to the CDC. In all, AIDS has struck more
than 61,000 people in the United States, killing more than 34,000
of them.
</TEXT>
