<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Names     05-14 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Names,0789</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREEHOLD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge ordered actor Peter O'Toole to
return his 5-year-old son to a former girlfriend by Tuesday or face
fines and possible arrest.
   Monmouth County Superior Court Judge Alexander Lehrer issued the
order Friday after Raoul Felder, an attorney for Karen Sommerville
O'Toole, requested an arrest order because O'Toole had not returned
his son, Lorcan, by a May 7 deadline.
   O'Toole and his former girlfriend, a Navesink resident who has
taken the 55-year-old actor's name but never married him, have
joint custody of the boy. Last December, they agreed to switch
custody of Lorcan every three months until September 1989, when
they hope to reach a long-term agreement.
   O'Toole took Lorcan to London in February.
   His attorney, Jeffrey Weinstein, said O'Toole held on to the boy
because Ms. Somerville O'Toole violated the custody agreement by
firing Lorcan's nanny. ``Peter was acting ... in the interests of
Lorcan,'' Weinstein said.
   Lehrer scheduled a hearing on the custody case for June 14.
   O'Toole faces $1,000 a day in fines if he does not comply with
the order, Felder and Weinstein said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Bob Hope says he's planning to
build a museum and entertainment complex near here featuring
mementoes from 50 years in show business.
   The complex will be built on 80 acres that Hope owns near Walt
Disney World, the 85-year-old entertainer said Friday.
   ``It's going to have all my memorabilia and movies from the past
50 years,'' Hope told WESH-TV in an interview from Los Angeles.
   Details on a design and an opening date have not been worked
out, Hope said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor-director Robert Redford has been keeping
busy during his journey to the Soviet Union.
   On Friday, he announced that Soviet scientists would attend a
conference on ecology this fall at the Institute for Resource
Management in Sundance, Utah, which he founded.
   He also said two Soviet movie makers would visit his Sundance
Institute for Independent Filmmakers next year to meet with U.S.
counterparts.
   Redford said the agreements resulted from meetings in the past
four days with prominent members of both professions.
   Redford, long active as an environmentalist, also moderated a
two-day conference on depletion of the ozone layer in the upper
atmosphere.
   Not everything, however, was conducted over a conference table.
Redford presided over the showing of eight of his movies in
Leningrad and Moscow. He was scheduled to put on more showings in
Tiblisi, the capital of Soviet Georgia, today and Sunday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Ned McWherter has appointed former
Miss America Kellye Cash the spokeswoman for state anti-drug ``Just
Say No'' clubs.
   ``I hope ... I can emphasize the value of organizing and working
together in our communities to help put an end to the abuse of
alcohol and other drugs,'' Miss Cash told a news conference Friday
shortly before a rally by about 500 ``Just Say No'' club members.
   The Memphis State University communications student and 1987
Miss America will help local groups with fund-raising projects to
raise $1 per school-age child for drug education and prevention
projects.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DUBUQUE, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The baseball movie ``Shoeless Joe'' has two
new members of its team _ Burt Lancaster and Ray Liotta.
   Lancaster will play Dr. Archibald Graham, who under the moniker
``Moonlight Graham'' played one inning of one game for the New York
Giants in 1905, said publicist Dave Fulton.
   Liotta, who appears in the current movie ``Dominick and
Eugene,'' will play the title character of Shoeless Joe Jackson,
the baseball star who was disgraced in the 1919 Chicago Black Sox
scandal.
   Filming in the Dubuque area is scheduled to begin May 31, Fulton
said recently.
   The story centers on an Iowa farmer who hears a voice telling
him that if he builds a baseball diamond in his cornfield, Shoeless
Joe will return to the game. Kevin Costner has already been cast as
the farmer.
   The female lead for the movie has not been chosen, Fulton said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Publisher Walter Annenberg donated $2 million
to Howard University's School of Communications to provide
scholarships and establish an endowed chair on the institution's
faculty, officials said.
   The donation Friday was the largest received from a living
person in the university's 120-year history, school officials said.
   Annenberg is president of Triangle Publications Inc., which
publishes Seventeen and TV Guide magazines and the Daily Racing
Form. He was U.S. ambassador to Britain from 1974 to 1978.
</TEXT>
