<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--China-Execution     05-14 0140</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--China-Execution,0143</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bicycle Thief Executed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 29-year-old man in the southern Chinese
province of Guangdong was executed for stealing 113 bicycles over
more than two years, an official newspaper reported today.
   The Legal Daily said the intermediate people's court of Shantou
had sentenced to death Xiao Guoqi, who was executed Friday, for
infringing on the legitimate property of citizens and jeopardizing
social order.
   It said Xiao stole $7,000 worth of bikes between March 1984 and
May 1986.
   An accomplice, Zheng Kundi, was sentenced to 13{ years in prison.
   China releases no figures on capital punishment, but is believed
to have executed more than 10,000 convicted criminals since
initiating an anti-crime drive in 1983. Murder, rape and multiple
thefts are among the most common crimes leading to execution,
normally a bullet to the back of the head.
</TEXT>
