<1ST_LINE>u i AM-BuildingCollapse 2ndLd-Writethru a0795 05-14 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Building Collapse, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0795,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rescuers Dig for Missing in Building Collapse; 13 Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-6 ```Hundreds of...Mexico City.'' to UPDATE with
two or three still trapped. Pickup 7th graf pvs ```Relatives
of...'''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AGUASCALIENTES, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers were called out Friday to
help dig for people missing in the rubble of a building collapse
that killed at least 13 the day before.
   Red Cross and state government officials confirmed the number
known dead and said 53 people were injured.
   Gilberto Sanchez, radio officer at police headquarters, said
about 60 soldiers from the army garrison joined firefighters,
police and volunteers in the rescue effort. Bulldozers and cranes
were brought from as far away as Salamanca, 78 miles to the
southwest.
   Aguascalientes, a city of about 500,000 people 320 miles
northwest of Mexico City, is the capital of Aguascalientes state.
   By late Friday, two or three people were believed still trapped
in the rubble, Celia de la Torre, a state government spokeswoman
said.
   Juan Diaz, head of special services for the local Red Cross,
said hundreds of people came to help in the rescue.
   At least 116 workers were in the building when the four upper
stories collapsed, said Diaz, reached by telephone from Mexico City.
   ``Relatives of the victims practically attacked the ambulances,
trying to identify'' the victims, he said.
   The building, still under construction, consisted of three
basements, a main floor and three upper stories.
   As workers were about to pour the last concrete late Thursday
afternoon, it collapsed onto a furniture factory that occupied the
ground floor and part of the basement area.
   Lower floors of buildings in Mexico often are occupied while the
upper stories are constructed.
   Roberto Padilla, an Aguascalientes state government spokesman,
said the state attorney general's office was investigating the
collapse of the building, which was three blocks from the main
plaza and the state capitol.
   Jorge Castaneda, head of the Aguascalientes Civil Engineers
Association, said a committee of engineers and architects also
would investigate.
   Juan Navarro, a police duty officer, said by telephone: ``They
were apparently pouring fresh concrete when it caved in. Apparently
the building did not resist the weight.''
   Juan Flores, a survivor who was buried for five hours, was
quoted by the Excelsior news agency as saying:
   ``I had finished working and was about to leave when ... all of
a sudden everyone started yelling hysterically that there was an
earthquake. I dashed under a table and all of a sudden everything
went dark, and there was this terrific noise and there was dust
everywhere.''
   He said a slab of concrete fell on the table and ``that is what
protected me from the rest of the debris.''
   Flores said he was quiet at first, but ``the fear and the
anguish of being buried ... impelled me to yell very loud, and the
rescue squads dug me out.'' Earlier Friday, the Red Cross had
reported 18 killed and 96 injured.
   Juan Manuel Diaz, the Red Cross duty officer at Aguascalientes,
said there had been confusion about reports from the scene. He did
not elaborate.
</TEXT>
