<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Taiwan     05-14 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Taiwan,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese, Taiwanese Musicians To Meet In U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Composers from China and Taiwan will meet in New
York in August in the first large-scale conference supported by
professional arts organizations from the two rival governments,
organizers say.
   In a release received in Beijing today, the Center for
U.S.-China Arts Exchange at Columbia University said 10 composers
each from China and Taiwan will take part in the Aug. 6-14
conference on ``Tradition and the Future of Chinese Music.''
   Center Director Chou Wen-chung said the 1987 relaxation of
restrictions on Taiwan residents visiting mainland China
contributed to a growing interest in cultural and educational
exchanges.
   ``Because the center is in touch with artists in both places, we
were aware that this moment offered an extraordinary opportunity,''
he said.
   Chou said he hoped the conference would lead to greater cultural
cooperation and contact in the arts between China and Taiwan.
   The Nationalist government on Taiwan has rejected all proposals
by Beijing for direct trade and cultural contacts. However,
Taipei's decision last year to let residents visit the mainland led
to a sharp increase in contacts between people on both sides of the
Taiwan Strait.
   The release said consultants who will help choose the conference
participants include Hsu Tsang-houei, chairman of the Chinese
Composers' League in Taiwan, and Wu Zuqiang, secretary-general of
the China Federation of Literary and Arts Circles.
   The center is the only U.S. agency dedicated solely to cultural
exchange with China. It brought Arthur Miller's ``Death of a
Salesman'' to China and was behind the Academy Award-winning film
``From Mao to Mozart: Isaac Stern in China.''
</TEXT>
