<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-ArtTroupes     05-14 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Art Troupes,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State to Drop Controls Over Art Troupes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is lifting controls on most art
troupes and will let individuals organize their own performing
groups, the official China Daily reported today.
   The daily quoted Culture Minister Wang Meng as saying state-run
art troupes will be replaced with a system that will permit free
and open competition among troupes. Performers will be allowed to
set their own box office prices and decide their own programs as
long as they are licensed and do not violate state laws and
regulations.
   Wang said the reforms are designed to stimulate the professional
enthusiam of the 200,000 people working in the nation's 3,094 art
troupes.
   He said many state-run troupes, where lifetime employment
prevails, are overstaffed, especially with those who are old and in
poor health.
   Wang said the state will continue to run a small number of the
country's best troupes or those needing special state support.
Among those are new experimental groups and groups in ethnic
minority areas.
   Wang said state-run troupes will also adopt a new salary system
with outstanding performers receiving better pay than those with
mediocre skills or past their prime.
   The state's decision to give up its monopoly over the arts has
drawn some criticism in the official press, with artists being
quoted as saying many traditional Chinese and minority musical,
dance and opera troupes are doomed by the ``survival of the
fittest'' policy.
   Concern has also been raised that troupes forced to pay their
own way will turn to sex, violence and superstition to draw
audiences.
</TEXT>
