<DOCNO> AP880514-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 0219EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BaldEagles     05-14 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bald Eagles,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bald Eagle Deaths Worrisome to Environmental Officials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The deaths of 10 bald eagles that
apparently ate illegally poisoned animal carcasses threaten the
comeback of the endangered birds in the Chesapeake Bay area,
federal officials said.
   ``While our national symbol is making a recovery, it cannot
sustain this rate of loss month after month nor will we tolerate
it,'' said Frank Dunkle, director of the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service.
   Five dead eagles, one adult and four immature bald eagles, were
found May 3 in a field near the carcasses of three raccoons, a deer
and a vulture. Five others were found elsewhere in Dorchester
County between March 12 and May 1, including the Blackwater
National Wildlife Refuge near Cambridge.
   ``The birds are not in danger of becoming extinct'' because of
illegal poisoning of animals, but ``the deaths resulting will have
some impact on their recovery because the deaths are occurring in
an area where we have a large amount of bald eagles,'' Glenn D.
Therres, the non-game and endangered species program manager for
the Maryland Forest, Park and Wildlife Service.
   State and federal officials said they are particularly concerned
because the county has the greatest concentration of bald eagles in
the Chesapeake Bay area. The eagle population, devastated by the
use of the pesticide DDT in the 1950s and 1960s, had been restored
to its highest levels on the East Coast.
   Officials are testing tissue from the dead eagles and the
carcasses for chemicals. Results are expected in several weeks, but
because the eagles had been dead at least a month before they were
found, such analyses can be difficult, said Inez Connor, a
spokeswoman for the Fish and Wildlife Service in Newton Corner,
Mass.
   ``The fact there has been a carcass near all of the eagles we
have found leads us to think that they died as a result of eating
poisoned animals,'' Ms. Connor said. Criminal charges could be
brought against anyone found to be poisoning animals. Bald eagles
are protected under federal law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
