<1ST_LINE>b i AM-Afghanistan-Blast     05-14 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan-Blast,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Truck Bomb Explodes Soviet Retreat Route, Killing Eight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded inside a truck early
Saturday near reviewing stands being prepared for farewell
ceremonies marking the Soviet withdrawal. Police said eight people
were killed and 20 injured.
   The blast occurred at 5:45 a.m. (9:15 p.m. EDT) in a housing
area on the banks of the Kabul River. Witnesses said they saw four
bodies being removed from a house that was destroyed.
   The blast demolished embankment walls on both sides of the river
that threads through the Afghan capital.
   Blood was visible on the gates of a nearby factory and personal
belongings, including carpet slippers, were scattered in the street.
   Witnesses said flames were visible when they arrived shortly
after the blast. The bomb had been planted in a large truck that
lay badly mangled at the scene.
   Last month, six people were killed and 49 wounded in another
bomb blast along the river banks on the 10th anniversary of the
April 1978 revolution that brought a Marxist government to power in
Afghanistan and triggered widespread insurrection.
   Soviet soldiers entered the war in December 1979 to help the
allied government fight off the anti-Communist rebels. About
115,000 remain here to back forces loyal to President Najib.
   But under an accord signed in Geneva on April 14, the Soviet
troops begin pulling out Sunday and are to complete the withdrawal
within nine months.
   Information for this account was based on a news agency pool
report from Kabul by Reuters. The Associated Press was not allowed
to go on the trip to Kabul because of questions it asked Najib in
the capital last month.
</TEXT>
