<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MemphisBarbecue Bjt   05-14 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Memphis Barbecue, Bjt,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grills Fire Up For Barbecue Cookoff</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clouds of smoke rose over the Mississippi
River bluffs as competitors fired up their cookers for Memphis'
annual barbecue contest, a weekend party of pork and beer billed as
the largest shindig of its kind.
   ``If you do him right, it'll take 24 hours,'' Fred Burnett of
Orlando, Fla., said Friday as he opened the side of his black iron
cooker to proudly display a 135-pound pig being turned into a
tender treat.
   ``We'll serve him with a spoon, not a knife,'' Burnett added.
   The cook-off, part of the city's annual Memphis In May Festival,
drew 175 cooking teams from around the country to compete in three
categories: whole hog, ribs and pork shoulder. Judging was set for
this afternoon, and the winners were to be announced tonight.
   Many of the teams, varying from three or four members to dozens,
also took part in a showmanship contest Friday. They staged skits
in costume outside their cooking booths, which ranged from simple
tents to elaborate two-story affairs and fully equipped kitchens
mounted on trailers.
   Barbecue cookers included plain iron drums and fancy customized
rigs.
   One team prepared its pork in a large metal cooker shaped like a
rabbit. Another relied on a bright red compact car gutted and lined
with iron to fashion a cooker.
   Keith Coleman, who owns a marine engine business in Memphis,
cooked his team's barbecue in what was once a 900-horsepower diesel
engine.
   Mounted on a 20-foot-long trailer with a built-in kitchen, the
shiny steel-and-iron rig cost about $20,000, Coleman said.
   ``We're ecologically sound. We catch our own waste and we're
totally self-contained,'' he said. ``When we get there, we're
there. We've got water. We've got electricity. Just add pork and
stir.''
   The contest is for pork cookers only, and Denise Bollheimer, a
spokeswoman for the 11-year-old event, said organizers were trying
for a world record for the amount of pork barbecue served in a
single day.
   The cook-off is billed as a ``world championship,'' but
organizers were trying for the first time to take a formal
accounting of the amount of meat cooked by the competitors. They
predicted the total would be in the tons.
   ``We've heard rumors that other contests are trying to claim
title as the largest, but we don't think they have a chance,'' Ms.
Bollheimer said. ``We will bask in the glory of knowing we're the
world's largest barbecue contest.''
   The Memphis In May Festival focuses on a different country each
year, and this year's guest was Great Britain, leading to numerous
Union Jacks and other British decorations at barbecue booths.
   One team, the Royal Kilted Kookers, included several members
from Scotland, even though their background as barbecue cookers was
limited.
   Tam White of Edinburgh said it was his first brush with American
barbecue.
   ``I tasted the ribs for the first time last night,'' White said.
``I found some meat on the bones and it was great. The only ribs
I'd had before were from a Chinese restaurant.''
</TEXT>
