<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     05-14 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sanitation Department has a new weapon in
its battle to keep the Big Apple clean _ the loud, high-pitched
voice of Mayor Edward I. Koch.
   Koch has made a tape-recording that will be played through
loudspeakers mounted on street-sweeping trucks that find their path
blocked by motorists.
   ``The Sanitation Department has to clean this street!'' it
blares. ``We can't because of your illegally parked car! Please get
it outta here!''
   Koch told reporters at City Hall on Friday that he wanted to
``tell motorists that I'm on their tail and I'm in the car
immediately behind them, and if they don't get out (of the way),
well, then we may just have to give them a summons. And they'll
expect me to get out of the truck and to give them a summons.''
   Asked if he actually will ride shotgun on a street sweeper, Koch
said, ``it hasn't occurred to me, but maybe.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of this exclusive city by the
sea will have to put up with the racket from tennis ball machines
if a city committee's recommendation goes through.
   The City Council's Ordinances, Rules and Standards Committee on
Thursday agreed to a compromise that would allow the use of the
machines at the same time heavy construction is permitted _ 9 a.m.
to 5:30 p.m. between Dec. 1 and April 3, and 8 a.m. to 6 p.m. the
rest of the year.
   Construction is banned on weekends, but the tennis ball machines
would not be.
   Since March, when the noise complaint issue arose, many
residents have urged the committee to ban the machines' use on
weekends.
   ``On an absolutely still summer evening, with no trains, no
airplanes and no boats going by, the tennis machines could
conceivably be very annoying because of their rhythmic thump,
thump, thump,'' said Councilman Paul Ilyinsky.
   The city council will take up the issue at its June 14 meeting.
</TEXT>
