<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SteinbeckAuction     05-14 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steinbeck Auction,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Author John Steinbeck's Effects To Be Auctioned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Furniture, paintings and other items that belonged
to the late John Steinbeck will be sold at auction next weekend,
says an estate broker hired by the author's sons.
   The furniture is nicked and scratched, knobs are missing from a
china cabinet and the frame is pulling away from an oil painting.
Some pieces seem vintage garage sale.
   ``We're not talking a great deal of monetary value on these
pieces,'' said Sylvia Link, a Denver estate broker and antiques
dealer who will conduct the sale at Estate Brokerage House on
Friday through Sunday.
   Steinbeck, author of ``The Grapes of Wrath'' and the 1962 Nobel
Prize winner, died in 1968.
   The sale has been commissioned by his sons, John, 41, and
Thomas, 43, who live in California. John lived in Boulder from 1979
to 1987, and his father's belongings remain stored there.
   The collection accounts for much of the author's estate, with
the exception of some silver sold earlier and items kept by the
family, according to John's wife, Nancy Steinbeck.
   The furniture and art is an eclectic mix, much of it American
and Oriental. Acquired by the man whose works, such as ``Cannery
Row'' and ``Of Mice and Men,'' were sympathetic to the common man,
the items reflect Steinbeck's apparent casual attitude toward
material possessions.
   A Chippendale corner cupboard normally would sell for about
$3,000. Because it belonged to Steinbeck, it probably will sell for
about $5,500, Link said.
</TEXT>
