<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FlyingSmoker     05-14 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Flying Smoker,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Investigates First Person for Breaking Smoking Ban</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Elly Brekke cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who admits sneaking a cigarette in an
airplane bathroom faces up to $4,000 in fines after becoming the
first person accused of violating the new ban on smoking aboard
short flights, officials said.
   ``He's not the first one to smoke on an airplane when they
weren't supposed to, but he's the first person to be accused of
breaking this new law,'' Federal Aviation Administration
spokeswoman Elly Brekke said Friday.
   Darryl Seigel, 38, of Seattle says he absent-mindedly began
smoking inside the lavatory during a 100-minute Seattle-to-Reno
flight on Thursday.
   ``It was an honest mistake,'' he said.
   A flight attendant spotted smoke coming from the lavatory after
Seigel left it about 20 minutes into the flight, said Rich Peacock,
spokesman for Reno Cannon Intenational Airport.
   The attendant asked Seigel if he knew about the federal law
against smoking on domestic flights of two hours or less, and then
told him he would be arrested when they landed.
   The flight attendant had explained the new law to passengers
before the plane took off.
   Airport security detained Seigel for two hours for questioning
at the request of the flight crew, Peacock said.
   Statements were taken Friday from the flight and maintenance
crews aboard the USAir plane Seigel was flying in, Brekke said. The
investigation should be completed within 60 days.
   Siegel faces three possible charges: Smoking when a no smoking
sign is on, which carries a $1,000 fine; smoking in the lavatory,
which also carries a $1,000 fine; and tampering with a lavatory
smoke detector, which carries a $2,000 fine.
   The federal smoking ban on short flights went into effect April
23.
</TEXT>
