<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NoPhones     05-14 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-No Phones,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Telephone Service Being Restored to Phoneless Area, Executive
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 35,000 suburban homes and businesses were
without telephone service today because of a fire at a switching
center, but about half probably will have intermittent dial tones
by Sunday, officials said.
   It will take until at least June before all the customers in
western suburbs will have full service, Illinois Bell vice
president James Eibel said Friday.
   ``We could have as many as 21,000 lines up in Hinsdale by the
end of this week, but it's not going to be the standard of service
that Illinois Bell wants to provide,'' Eibel said.
   ``That's my most optimistic view if everything absolutely goes
right _ and, frankly, it will not,'' Eibel added.
   Technicians originally thought the digital switching device
damaged by smoke and water in the fire Sunday could be repaired,
but Eibel said Illinois Bell has decided to purchase a new one from
AT&T. There were no injuries in the fire.
   A telephone systems analyst told the Chicago Tribune on Friday
that such a switch could cost as much as $16 million.
   Meanwhile, State Rep. James R. Stange introduced a House
resolution Friday calling for an investigation of the fire by a
special legislative committee.
   ``It has devastated hundreds of businesses, many of which place
catalog orders such as Spiegel and those which operate 800 numbers
like Holiday Inn,'' Stange said.
   ``Our whole economy has been temporarily staggered. Gas
stations, airports, hospitals, restaurants, delivery services,
brokerage houses _ you name it _ all have suffered,'' Stange said.
</TEXT>
