<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChildPreacher     05-14 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Child Preacher,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Street Preacher Suspended Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARION, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dispute over a 10-year-old Bible-quoting
schoolyard preacher, who was suspended a fourth time after he
refused to stop proselytizing and go to class, will wind up in
court, his mother says.
   ``It's gone too far now,'' Robin Strode said Friday after her
son, Duffey Strode, received his fourth suspension from Eastfield
Elementary School in this tiny town in the Blue Ridge Mountains of
western North Carolina.
   Duffey, surrounded by dozens of reporters, stood in the school
parking lot Friday morning, ignoring requests from Assistant
Principal Shirley Ramsey that he stop preaching and come in out of
the rain.
   He accused onlookers of various sins.
   ``Thou shall not take the name of the Lord thy God in vain!''
Duffey shouted. ``Thou shalt not commit adultery! You're guilty!
Even your eyes are filled with adultery! Men can't keep their eyes
off women and women can't keep their eyes off men. Adulterers shall
be put to death and their blood shall be upon them!''
   After several minutes, Mrs. Ramsey left Duffey standing on the
sidewalk and went into the school. After talking to his mother, he
entered the building to hand in some homework. Five minutes later,
the boy emerged, carrying a letter of suspension.
   The letter did not mention preaching, but said Duffey was
suspended for 10 days for being insubordinate, refusing to abide by
school policies, refusing to accompany Mrs. Ramsey into the school
and disruptive behavior.
   Duffey appeared unrepentent. ``I'd rather get gold and silver up
in heaven than an education down here,'' he said.
   ``This thing's going to court,'' Mrs. Strode said. She said she
has contacted an attorney through the Rutherford Institute, which
she described as a non-profit Christian legal foundation based in
Manassass, Va.
   Duffey's brother, Matthew, 5, and sister, Pepper, 6, also were
suspended for defying school officials earlier this month.
   Mrs. Strode said they probably will be suspended again when they
return to school Thursday.
   ``I told them if they want to go back and preach, that's fine,''
she said in an interview at the family's home.
   Mrs. Strode blames the family's problems on school officials.
   ``They are the ones who are keeping my children from getting an
education,'' she said.
   Mrs. Ramsey said the Strode children could return to school
Monday if they would agree to stop shouting Bible verses on school
grounds. She said expulsion was unlikely since the school year was
almost over.
   But Mrs. Strode said she couldn't guarantee Duffey would quit
preaching.
   ``I just leave that up to him, and if he wants to preach, I'll
back him 100 percent,'' she said. ``And if he doesn't, that's fine,
too.''
   Earlier, when asked if he felt pressured by parents, Duffey had
said, ``No. They ain't. I want to do it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
