<HEAD>Four Mental Health Workers Placed on Leave Following Newborn's
Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four staff members have been put on temporary
leave at Chicago-Read Mental Health Center while officials
investigate the death of a newborn girl who drowned in a toilet
last month, state officials say.
   The workers were suspended last week and will continue to
receive paychecks, Dave Devane, spokesman for the Illinois
Department of Mental Health, said Friday.
   ``Our investigators are still talking to people,'' Devane said.
``Several other actions might be taken by the time the whole matter
is concluded in about two weeks.''
   Devane said there would be no criminal charges filed against the
newborn's mother or anyone else involved. He declined to comment
further on what other actions the department might be considering.
   The death prompted several mental-health advocacy groups to
accuse the department of chronic underfunding and understaffing of
its facilities.
   But Devane said hospital staff members checked the 34-year-old
woman before she had given birth, about 15 minutes before the
infant was found in the toilet.
   Staff members found the child after they saw blood on the
mother's leg, he said. An autopsy showed the newborn had drowned.
