<HEAD>Sinatra Blasts `Kiss-And-Tell' Books</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note language may be objectionable</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank Sinatra says the people who write
``kiss-and-tell'' books such as those written about President
Reagan by former aides are ``pimps and whores.''
   The people who write such books ``can't write their own name to
earn a living properly,'' Sinatra said in an interview telecast
Friday on Larry King's Cable News Network talk show.
   ``They've got to lean on somebody else, and they know nothing
about the person of whom they've written,'' said the 72-year-old
singer. ``Those are the pimps and whores.''
   Former White House Chief of Staff Donald Regan and former Reagan
press secretary Larry Speakes recently published books that told
unflattering tales about the president.
   ``They're the ones who write the books about people with whom
they had a kind of privy association and believed in them and
believed in the other guy and suddenly they're out making a buck
because they got a pigeon,'' he added.
   Sinatra is a friend of President and Nancy Reagan.
   The entertainer also said a recent unauthorized biography he had
unsuccessfully tried to block had not made him feel bad.
   ``It didn't really sting me that much,'' he said. ``I've been
whacked around before, and came through pretty good.''
</TEXT>
