<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0489,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Showers, Thunderstorms Fall Over Broad Area</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, ``High-temperature records ...,'' to DELETE
redundant reference to Tucson, Ariz.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms stretched across a broad area today
from southern New England into Pennsylvania, Kentucky and Missouri
after heavy rains closed some roads.
   Showers and thunderstorms also covered much of Florida, and
showers lingered over southern Georgia and the Carolina coast.
   A few showers and thunderstorms continued ahead of a cold front
crossing the northern High Plains. Scattered showers dampened the
Pacific Northwest. Fair skies prevailed over the rest of the nation.
   Thunderstorms Friday night forced the closing of some roads in
Trimble County, Ky.
   Strong, gusty winds blew through the Great Plains. In Wyoming on
Friday night, winds gusted to 58 mph in Rawlins and hit 62 mph in
Cody.
   High-temperaure records were set in a number of cities,
including Casper, Wyo., where a reading of 85 degrees topped by 1
degree the mark set in 1941. Temperature records fell in Tucson,
Ariz., where it was 105 degrees, 2 degrees higher than the 1978
record for the date; Billings, Mont., 87 (85, 1969); Alamosa,
Colo., 81 (80, 1984).
   A cold front moving eastward across the country caused
temperatures to plunge today. In Montana, the mercury had dropped
as much as 40 degrees by early today. Temperatures ahead of the
cold front were still in the 60s and low 70s in the south central
region and the Southeast.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
Florida to the Carolina coast; scattered showers and thunderstorms
from Tennessee and the upper Mississippi Valley to the northern and
central Plains to Colorado; a few showers over Washington and
Oregon and windy conditions prevailing over the northern Rockies
and northern Plains.
   High temperatures were expected to be in the 70s or 80s over
much of the nation; in the 50s or 60s from New England to the Great
Lakes region and from the northern Rockies to the Pacific
Northwest; the 90s over the central and southern Plains; and from
the 90s to near 110 degrees in the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 28
degrees at Sawyer Air Force Base in Marquette, Mich., to 87 degrees
at Yuma, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 62 partly cloudy; Boston 58 windy; Buffalo 44
fair; Charleston, S.C. 67 rain; Cincinnati 55 fair; Cleveland 46
fair; Detroit 46 fair; Miami 71 cloudy; New York 61 partly cloudy;
Philadelphia 64 partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 51 partly cloudy;
Portland, Maine 50 fair; Washington 63 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 53 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 65 fair; Denver 60
fair; Des Moines 57 fair; Indianapolis 56 fair; Kansas City 64
fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 46 fair; Nashville 68 partly cloudy; New
Orleans 66 fair; St. Louis 63 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 69 fair; Anchorage 48 cloudy; Las Vegas 76
fair; Los Angeles 62 fair; Phoenix 86 fair; Salt Lake City 49 fair;
San Diego 60 foggy; San Francisco 54 windy; Seattle 49 rain.
   _Canada: Montreal 41 fair; Toronto 37 fair.
</TEXT>
