<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 0711EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChryslerContract     05-14 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chrysler Contract,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UAW: Contracts Stand As-is Despite Skilled Trades Rejection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Auto Workers' contracts with Chrysler
Corp. will stand despite a narrow rejection by skilled trades
workers of a pact ratified by a majority of 66,000 union members,
UAW leaders say.
   ``The International Executive Board after reviewing all the
issues ... has determined that this contract stands properly
ratified,'' the union said Friday in a statement attributed to UAW
President Owen Bieber and Vice President Marc Stepp.
   The contract was ratified by 54 percent of the vote Wednesday.
Skilled trades workers, who have an additional, separate contract
but cast a single vote for or against both pacts, narrowly rejected
it.
   Chrysler says it has about 10,500 active skilled trades workers.
   Delegates to the UAW's 140-member national Chrysler council who
represent skilled trades workers met in Chicago on Friday with
Stepp and other union leaders to determine whether negotiations
should resume.
   The union and Chrysler could have returned to the bargaining
table to discuss skilled trades issues if those had been behind the
rejection. However, if the rejection was on issues in the main
contract, such as economics, then the UAW would take no further
action.
   The union's decision indicated that the rejection concerned the
main contract. Union officials had said before the meeting that
they believed the rejection was economic, and blamed it on a $1,000
signing bonus.
   Chrysler workers received a $2,120 bonus in 1985 for signing a
three-year contract.
   The UAW executive board, which includes Bieber, Stepp, other UAW
vice presidents and regional directors, decided to ratify the
contract after receiving a report on the Chicago meeting.
   The contracts, reached May 5 after 2{ weeks of early
negotiations, cover 66,000 hourly and salaried Chrysler workers in
15 states.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
