<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ElderlySlaying     05-14 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Elderly Slaying,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Convicted in Rape, Fatal Burning of Elderly Woman</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was convicted of murder in an attack on
a 65-year-old woman who was raped and robbed before being tied to a
bed and burned to death.
   A Superior Court jury deliberated less than two days before
pronouncing Manuel Mendoza, 23, of Alhambra, guilty Friday of one
count each of murder, rape, arson and robbery in the Feb. 7, 1986,
assault on Mary Frances Litovitch.
   Mendoza faces either a life sentence in prison without parole or
the death penalty, Deputy District Attorney Lauren Weis said. A
separate hearing will be held to determine the jury's sentencing
recommendation.
   Mendoza also was convicted of nine other felonies, including
robbery, burglaries and kidnappings that occurred from Feb. 5 to
Feb. 7, Weis said.
   Evidence presented by the prosecutor showed that Mendoza broke
into Litovich's home during the afternoon and sexually assaulted
her. After tying her to the posts of a bed, he attempted to
strangle her, breaking her neck, then poured a flammable liquid
over the bed and set it ablaze.
   Neighbors heard Litovich's screams and tried to rescue her as
smoke billowed from her bedroom. But she died before they could
reach her.
   Mendoza later was arrested after a neighbor reported seeing him
fleeing with a case later identified as Litovich's camera case. The
case, later recovered, contained some of the woman's jewelry, Weis
said.
</TEXT>
