<1ST_LINE>d a PM-NosotrosAwards     05-14 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nosotros Awards,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Awards For Hispanic Roles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The movie ``La Bamba'' swept the Golden Eagle
Awards at the 18th annual Nosotros Banquet, which honors
achievements and contributions by Hispanics in entertainment.
   At Friday night's gala, the most promising actor and actress
awards went to Lou Diamond Phillips and Rosana de Soto, who star in
the movie about the short life of 1950s rocker Richie Valens.
   ``La Bamba'' director Luis Valdez was named outstanding director
for the film, which was released in both English and Spanish last
summer.
   Los Lobos, the band whose version of the Valens hit ``La Bamba''
climbed to the top of the record charts last year, won the music
achievement award.
   Other winners included Charlie Sheen, named outstanding actor
for his performance in the movie ``Wall Street,'' and Raquel Welch,
who won outstanding actress.
   She starred as the determined barmaid mother who filed legal
actions to remove a racist teacher from her daughter's high school
in the NBC-TV movie ``Scandal in a Small Town.''
   Jaime Escalante, the Garfield High School math teacher whose
success in teaching students calculus was dramatized in the movie
``Stand and Deliver,'' was named winner of a lifetime achievement
award, as was the musical group Las Hermanas Padilla. The group has
been performing for more than 50 years.
   Eddie Velez and Elizabeth Pena were named outstanding television
actor and actress. Velez's series, ``Trial and Error,'' was
canceled by CBS.
   Kenny Ortega, the choreographer for the movie ``Salsa'' and
``Dirty Dancing'' was named outstanding choreographer, while singer
Jose Feliciano was named outstanding performer.
   The Nosotros group was founded in 1980 by actor Ricardo
Montalban and others interested in promoting Hispanics in
entertainment.
</TEXT>
