<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Ferries,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ferry Workers Abandon Sympathy Strikes for Dover Colleagues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOVER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ferry services around Britain began
resuming normal operations after unionized workers ended walkouts
that had been called in support of a strike by ferry workers in
Dover.
   The National Union of Seaman instructed its members to end its
sympathy strikes on Friday. The strikes had been called in support
of a 14-week-old walkout by workers at P and O European Ferries in
Dover.
   Truck drivers angered at the disruption of freight traffic by
the strikes also ended on Thursday their four-day blockade of ferry
loading berths in English, French and Belgian ports.
   Thousands of ferry workers in more than a dozen British ports,
including some 2,300 Sealink British Ferries workers in Dover, had
walked out in recent weeks in sympathy with their P and O
colleagues.
   P and O workers struck in February to protest new work
conditions extending the work week.
   P and O, the largest channel operator, wants to streamline
operations before the undersea Channel Tunnel between England and
France opens in 1993.
