<1ST_LINE>r i PM-People-Karajan 1stLd-Writethru a0461 05-14 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Karajan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0461,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Senate to Debate Karajan as Criticism of Conductor Grows</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to fix typo in Berlin; SUBS 6th graf, ``He
canceled xxx, to delete extraneous 10-</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Berlin Philharmonic conductor Herbert von
Karajan's frequent absences and canceled West Berlin concerts have
struck a chorus of sour notes from once-loyal Berliners and will be
taken up by the city's Senate.
   The council said Friday that it would debate those issues May 30.
   A Social Democratic delegate to the Senate, Walter Momper, said
it would also examine recording and other contracts made by
Karajan's agent that may involve work by the entire Berling
Philharmonic.
   ``Berlin and its orchestra are not a vehicle that exists solely
to advance Karajan's economic interests,'' he told reporters.
   Karajan, the orchestra's 80-year-old ``conductor for life,'' has
been sharply criticized in recent months by Berlin fans and city
cultural officials who disburse the public funds that help bankroll
the orchestra.
   He canceled a heavily advertised Berlin concert on Sunday, April
24, then flew off to Japan for a tour with the orchestra the next
day, provoking widespread complaints from Berliners.
   Karajan has suffered medical problems in recent years, including
severe back pains that have forced him to cancel conducting
appearances. But city cultural officials say he has on several
occasions called off concerts under questionable circumstances.
   During a tour of West Germany last November, Karajan called off
a concert appearance in Duesseldorf, saying he couldn't mount the
podium because he said he had food poisoning from eating tainted
fish.
   Karajan later changed his mind and performed, but called off
another appearance in Stuttgart during the same tour.
   Michael Dieterici, a city Cultural Affairs office spokesman,
recently told The Associated Press that West Berlin provides some
$25 million in subsidies to the orchestra. He said he did not know
how much money Karajan receives directly.
   West German publications have recently carried reports about
enormous sums of money Karajan's agents allegedly demanded last
year for a concert tour of Taiwan. The tour was later called off
because of the fees Karajan was demanding, according to the reports.
</TEXT>
