<DOCNO> AP880514-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 0906EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Violence     05-14 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Violence,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pro-Iranian Forces Assault Syrian-backed Beirut Foes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pro-Iranian fundamentalists today
attacked the last stronghold of their Syrian-backed rivals in the
city's southern slums, where the two factions have waged a bloody
duel for control since May 6.
   Police said six people were killed and 13 wounded in today's
inter-Shiite Moslem fighting, lifting the nine-day toll to 204
killed and 574 wounded.
   In other fighting today in the southern neighborhoods, Palestine
Liberation Organization chairman Yasser Arafat's loyalist
guerrillas and Syrian-backed adversaries traded mortar and
artillery fire at the Bourj el-Barajneh refugee camp.
   Police said three people were killed and 11 wounded in the
fighting between Arafat's mainstream Fatah guerrillas and rebels
led by Col. Saeed Mousa.
   There was no word on what started the fighting at the refugee
camp, where billows of smoke rose from the gunfire. The intense
battles in the area, where the pro-Syrian Amal and the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah were also fighting, kept reporters out.
   A police spokesman said Hezbollah launched a pre-dawn assault on
the Shiyah district, seeking to dislodge Amal of its last
stronghold in the area. The thuds of exploding shells echoed across
west Beirut as the two factions battled with heavy artillery,
mortar and tank fire.
   Hezbollah said in a statement that its fighters were advancing
into Shiyah. Amal spokesmen said the assault was repulsed and that
a counter-attack was launched to retake positions captured by
Hezbollah.
   Police said they were unable to verify the claims.
   The two groups were fighting in a 16-square-mile enclave where
most of the 18 foreign hostages were believed held by kidnappers
affiliated with Hezbollah, or Party of God. The Beirut-based weekly
magazine Ash-Shiraa said Friday the hostages had been moved from an
exposed Hezbollah barracks to the home of Sheik Ibrahim al-Amin,
Hezbollah's spokesman, in a less vulnerable neighborhood.
   Ash-Shiraa was first to report in November 1986 on the secret
U.S. arms sales to Iran made in an effort to free the hostages, who
include nine Americans.
   Syria, meanwhile, escalated its war of words with Hezbollah. A
ranking Syrian official said, ``Hezbollah has become an aberration
on the Lebanese scene.
   ``This phenomenon is destabilizing tranquility and warrants
immediate and drastic treatment,'' the official told the Moslem
Voice of Nation radio without elaborating. The broadcast did not
identify the official.
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, maintains 25,000 troops
in the Bekaa and in north Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League
peacekeeping mandate. Though Iran's main Arab ally, Syria has been
alarmed by Tehran's attempt through Hezbollah to dominate Lebanon's
1.2 million Shiites.
   Police estimate Hezbollah has 3,000 combatants fighting Amal,
which has thrown some 6,500 militiamen into the battle.
   Hezbollah also said Amal's military headquarters on the main
Beirut Airport highway were overrun during the night. Amal denied
the claim.
   Hezbollah's snipers killed a Syrian on the airport highway on
Friday and Syrian soldiers fired back, killing five Hezbollah
fighters. It was the first time that the Syrians directly
intervened in the fighting, which falls outside their jurisdiction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
