<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea-Protest     05-14 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Protest,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korean Police Clash with Reunification Protesters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Student protesters today hurled rocks
and firebombs as police set off barrages of tear gas to break up a
march advocating reunification talks with North Korea.
   There were no immediate reports of arrests or injuries.
   The march broke off from a rally of about 10,000 students from
universities around the country who gathered at Korea University.
   Some prominent dissident leaders, including the Rev. Moon
Ik-hwan, attended the rally. Relatives of hundreds of jailed
dissidents also participated.
   The students, many wearing headbands reading ``unification,''
also asked the government of President Roh Tae-woo to make
concessions to persuade North Korea to join the Seoul Olympic Games
in the fall.
   In a separate statement, the demonstrators proposed that student
leaders of South and North Korea meet on June 10 to discuss
national unification and the Olympic co-hosting.
   Unification of the Korean Peninsula has emerged as a major
campus issue as radical students shifted their anti-government
strategy after legislative elections last month, when the
opposition made a strong showing.
   North Korea has said it would boycott the Olympics in Seoul
unless it is allowed to co-host the Games.
   After the campus rally, about 5,000 students walked out of the
school to begin what they called ``a grand peace march'' to
headquarters of the National Red Cross in downtown Seoul.
   When the marchers went 1,000 yards, about 2,000 riot police
intervened, pushing the students to both sides of the street. Some
students responded by throwing rocks.
   Many protesters were forced back to the school, where they began
throwing hundreds of firebombs and rocks over the fence. Police
retaliated with tear gas.
</TEXT>
