<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Obit-Baker 1stLd-Writethru   05-14 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Baker, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0459,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jazz Trumpeter Chet Baker Dies In Fall From Building</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with police saying Baker used heroin
before death. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American trumpeter Chet Baker, a
jazz virtuoso who found fame in the 1950s but whose career was
haunted by heroin addiction, died in a fall from the second floor
of his hotel.
   Baker, who was 59, took heroin just before he fell from the
hotel window shortly after 3:10 a.m. Friday, police spokesman Klaas
Wilting said today. Authorities found Baker dead in the street.
   Wilting said suicide was possible. But Ria Wigt of Wigt
Productions, Baker's worldwide agent, said Baker ``wasn't the type
of man'' who would commit suicide.
   Born Chesney Baker in Yale, Okla., in 1929, the musician set the
standard for what jazz buffs knew as the ``cool school.''
   In 1952, he was working with Charlie Parker on the West Coast
when he joined the piano-less quartet of British saxophonist Gerry
Mulligan.
   With his good looks and youth and fragile, introverted tone,
Baker soon became a cult figure. In 1953, he topped the Metronome
trumpet poll and started his own quartet. His work became more
assured and outgoing.
   Baker looked something like actor James Dean and sounded
something like famed jazz trumpeter Bix Beiderbecke. As a player,
Miles Davis was his main inspiration.
   In 1955, Baker took a group to Europe that showed high promise.
Then his career started to suffer. An Italian court sentenced him
to a 16-month prison term in 1960 for drug possession.
   In San Francisco in 1968, Baker said he was beaten up by
hoodlums and suffered severe injuries that included the loss of his
teeth, a trumpet player's nightmare.
   For two years Baker didn't play, but he said recently he had
quit drugs. He began recording again and made an album with pop
star Elvis Costello.
   In 1974, critic John S. Wilson wrote in The New York Times that
Baker had developed ``more range and assertiveness within the
wistfully ruminative style with which he has also been associated.''
   Baker had scheduled several appearances in the Netherlands as
part of a tour that also included West Berlin and France.
   He had been staying at the Prins Hendrik hotel close to
Amsterdam's drug district, said Wilting.
   ``The way it looks, he had just been using'' heroin, Wilting
told The Associated Press. Traces of heroin use were found in
Baker's hotel room, he added.
   ``Maybe he started acting funny,'' said Wilting. ``He was alone
and shoved the window open himself and either fell or jumped out _
I don't suppose we'll ever find out which.''
   A receptionist at the hotel, where Baker checked in Thursday,
said the musician ``was a little nervous'' when he arrived. He did
not elaborate.
   The receptionist, who refused to give his name, said the window
of Baker's room slides open vertically, leaving a 10-inch gap at
most.
   ``How he got through there I don't know,'' the receptionist
said. ``He must have been dead straight away,'' he said.
   The hotel official said Baker showed no signs of drug abuse.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880514-0068 </DOCNO>
