<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gorbachev-Americans     05-14 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev-Americans,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Letters to Gorbachev Intended for Book</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans sent more than 80,000 letters to Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev last year, and the ``most
characteristic'' of the messages will be published in a book, a
Soviet newspaper reported Saturday.
   Sovietskaya Kultura published excerpts of 13 letters from across
the United States and an introduction that will be included in the
book.
   The book will be called ``Americans Write to Gorbachev,'' which
was also the headline on top of Saturday's newspaper story. The
letter excerpts mostly expressed the writers' concerns about world
peace and the threat of nuclear war, but they also touched on
topics like Stalinism and the aims of socialism.
   Vitaly Korotich, editor of the weekly news magazine Ogonyok,
described the American missives as ``letters of hope.'' Korotich
and Soviet affairs scholar Stephen Cohen of Princeton University
discussed the mail and its meaning in a dialogue that will
accompany the letters selected for the book.
   Sovietskaya Kultura did not say when the book would be available.
</TEXT>
