<DOCNO> AP880514-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1108EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Noriega 2ndLd-Writethru a0466 05-14 0759</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Noriega, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0466,720</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 11th graf, As he, to include Dole
comment; edits following graf for transition.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III has told
President Reagan he shared objections by prosecutors to dismissing
drug trafficking charges against Panamanian military leader Manuel
Antonio Noriega, one of the prosecutors says.
   Meese ``told me that he also opposed'' any dismissal and ``he
would convey my thoughts to the president,'' U.S. Attorney Leon
Kellner of Miami said Friday after meeting with the attorney
general in Washington.
   ``He did that today,'' Kellner said.
   U.S. Attorney Robert W. Merkle, whose office in Tampa obtained
one of two drug indictments against Noriega in February, said from
Florida if he were ordered to sign an order dismissing charges
against Noriega, ``They wouldn't have to fire me, I would resign.''
   ``I could not myself sign an order of dismissal, but I may not
be in a position to stop it,'' Merkle said Friday in his first
public comment about the negotitations reportedly going on to
remove the military leader from power.
   Reagan administration officials have said they were ``plea
bargaining'' with the Panamanian military chief and de facto ruler
over the possible dropping of drug-smuggling indictments returned
in February by grand juries in Miami and Tampa, Fla.
   The State Department apparently believes that dismissal of the
indictments is the only way to induce Noriega's departure, but the
Justice Department sees that concession as too high a price to pay.
   But Kellner said dismissing the case would ``send the wrong
message to the people of this country.''
   ``What it says is that the bigger you are and if you have more
threats to give to this country, we'll let you get away with
criminality,'' Kellner said, explaining his objections.
   ``How do we continue ... going after the little fish when the
big fish can walk away?'' he said, referring in particular to the
Colombia-based Medellin cartel.
   As he has since word of a possible deal with Noriega leaked out
Wednesday, Meese told reporters he would have no comment on the
matter.
   Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., today lauded the administration's
objective of getting rid of Noriega but said the charges against
him must stand. ``Letting him off the hook would send exactly the
wrong message at exactly the wrong time to the world's drug
king-pins, the peddlers of death and misery,'' said the former
presidential candidate in a statement released by his office.
   At the White House on Friday, presidential spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater was asked about assertions by Noriega that negotiations
with the United States on his eventual departure from power have
collapsed.
   ``He says that all the time,'' Fitzwater said. ``He said `fall
apart' or something similar before.
   ``We are still talking. We are still negotiating.''
   Fitzwater said Elliott Abrams, assistant secretary of state for
inter-American affairs, met with Reagan on Friday afternoon. He
would not say what the subject of the meeting was or who else, if
anyone, attended.
   The president left for his weekend at Camp David a half-hour
later than originally scheduled, but Fitzwater would not say
whether the meeting caused the delay.
   Earlier Friday, Panama's foreign minister denied that Noriega
was negotiating to have the drug charges dropped.
   Panamanian Foreign Minister Jorge Ritter, interviewed on
ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America,'' said no deal involving Noriega
was imminent and the drug indictment ``isn't really part of the
negotiations.'' He did not elaborate on what was being discussed.
   A top State Department official, Michael Kozak, has been engaged
in secret negotiations with Noriega in Panama, and administration
sources said Wednesday the military chieftain was told that if he
left Panama for a year, perhaps in August, the indictments would be
dropped.
   However, Noriega said Friday night, ``I have not talked with Mr.
Kozak,'' and he called for the U.S. ambassador to Panama to leave
the country.
   ``The dignity of Panama is not negotiable while there are
foreign troops on our territory, humiliating our soil, while there
is economic aggression, as long as there are threats, as long as
there is psychological war ... as long as Ambassador Arthur Davis
does not get out,'' Noriega said during a meeting in Rio Hato, 60
miles southwest of Panama City.
   State Department spokeswoman Sondra McCarty said she had no
comment on Noriega's statements or whether the United States was
considering withdrawing Davis from Panama.
   Noriega has survived widespread public protests and an economic
collapse at home as well as sustained U.S. diplomatic and economic
pressure.
</TEXT>
