<DOCNO> AP880514-0080 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1114EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CollapsingContras Bjt   05-14 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Collapsing Contras, Bjt,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels May Face Disintegration, Officials Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nicaraguan Contras, poorly supplied and
politically divided, may face disintegration, with impact beyond
Nicaragua's borders, according to U.S. officials.
   Less than two months after the rebels signed a temporary
cease-fire agreement with Nicaragua's leftist government,
administration analysts on Central America say the Contras' future
seems bleak for a variety of reasons:
   _Up to 3,000 rebels, denied delivery of U.S. humanitarian aid
shipments, have fled across the Nicaraguan border into Honduras in
search of food.
   _Serious rifts have emerged in the Contra ranks. An undetermined
number of rebels mutinied recently against military commander
Enrique Bermudez at a Contra camp in southern Honduras. Bermudez
also faces opposition from at least two members of the rebel
political directorate.
   _If fighting resumes after the current cease fire ends on June
1, the Contras have enough military supplies to last only one to
two months. Congress rejected President Reagan's military aid
request on Feb. 3 and there is little support at present for a
reversal of that decision.
   _Soviet military supplies are continuing to flow to the
Sandinistas at a rate slightly ahead of the 1987 pace. According to
U.S. estimates, Soviet military deliveries totaled $105 million for
the first three months of 1988.
   ``The Contras seem to be in the process of disintegrating,''
said one official, insisting on anonymity. ``The consolidation of
Sandinista rule is upon us.''
   The official said all of the predictions he and some others in
the administration had made in February after the congressional
rejection of Contra aid are being borne out.
   Specifically, he said the aid vote has contributed to increasing
right-left political polarization in Guatemala, reflected in a
failed military coup attempt there last week, and in El Salvador,
where the rightist ARENA party won impressively in national
elections in March, the official said.
   He added that the prospective demise of the U.S.-backed rebels
in Nicaragua has had the effect of ``emboldening'' leftist
guerrillas in El Salvador who are aligned with the Sandinistas.
   These views, however, are not universally shared in the
administration. Another official, also speaking privately, said the
trends in Guatemala and El Salvador are the result of internal
developments unrelated to the situation in Nicaragua.
   The prevailing view among more conservative members of the
administration is that consolidation of Sandinista rule would
generate nervousness in neighboring countries, forcing them to
shift priorities from democratic development to concerns over
internal security.
   If military coups occur, Congress would retaliate by drastically
reducing assistance, creating both economic hardship and increasing
sympathy for leftist rebels, according to this scenario.
   The Contras and the Sandinistas signed a temporary truce in
Sapoa, Nicaragua, on March 23. They agreed to try to negotiate a
permanent cease-fire during a 60-day period starting April 1.
   With the deadline for reaching agreement on formally ending
their six-year war just two weeks away, there has been virtually no
progress toward that objective.
   Disputes between the Sandinistas and the Contras have prevented
delivery of U.S. humanitarian aid to the rebels inside Nicaragua,
leaving the administration with no option but to try to send them
cash via couriers.
   If no final agreement is reached by the June 1 deadline, the
Contras have two obvious alternatives available to them, neither
very promising, the officials said.
   As one official described it, the Contras could resume the war
and face defeat against superior Sandinista firepower. Or they
could reach agreement with the Sandinistas on a truce extension,
enabling the Sandinistas to maintain slow-pace negotiations in
hopes that total demoralization of the rebels eventually would set
in.
   If the Sandinistas decide to resume the war, this would win
renewed sympathy for the rebels in the U.S. Congress but the
Contras also could be confronted with what one official said was
the possibility of a quick ``knockout blow.''
   In that case, he said, ``if the Congress decides to approve more
aid, there would be no one to give the aid to.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880514-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-South Bjt   05-14 1011</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-South, Bjt,1,000</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Looms As Tough Battleground For Democratic Nominee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The South, once solidly Democratic in
presidential races but now reliably Republican, is a tough
battleground for Michael Dukakis as he tries to put together an
electoral coalition to defeat George Bush and enable the party to
recapture the White House.
   With many states in the politically conservative region viewed
as beyond his reach in November, Dukakis is being urged to choose a
running mate who could help the Democrats carry Texas or Florida,
the two largest states south of the Mason-Dixon line.
   Dukakis won the Democratic primaries in both those states on
Super Tuesday, a fact that gives Democrats reason for optimism.
   Supporters of the Massachusetts governor also are quick to argue
that Bush does not have the hold on Southern voters that Ronald
Reagan could claim.
   It's possible for Dukakis to find the 270-vote Electoral College
majority outside the South, a coalition that would require every
big industrial state in the North plus California and Farm Belt
states where economic hard times the past seven years have made the
Reagan-Bush administration politically unpopular.
   But any Dukakis strategy without the South would require an
electoral shift of historic proportions for a Democratic victory in
November.
   ``They cannot let us sweep it (the South),'' said Vince Breglio,
a Republican consultant and authority on electoral college
strategies. ``If we take Florida, Texas, Georgia, North Carolina
and the rest of the cotton South, I don't think they can win.''
   ``What I can't figure out is how you get the numbers if you
don't run strong in the South,'' said Walter F. Mondale, the 1984
Democratic presidential nominee.
   Mitch Daniels, who served President Reagan as White House
political director, predicted that the Democrats would ``decide the
South is a mirage and that their best hope lies in a sweep of the
industrial belt.''
   Larry Sabato, a political scientist at the University of
Virginia, said that if the political trends go in Dukakis'
direction and he is headed for a big victory he would run well in
the South, but ``if it's a close election, I'd say he has very
little hope of carrying much outside of perhaps a couple of border
states.''
   For generations, 16 Southern and border states gave Democratic
presidential candidates a solid electoral base. In 1944, Franklin
D. Roosevelt took all 167 electoral votes from those states.
   Dwight D. Eisenhower broke the Democratic hold on the region in
1952 and 1956. And in 1964, when Democrat Lyndon B. Johnson crushed
Sen. Barry Goldwater, the only bright spot for the Arizona
Republican was the Deep South. Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana,
Mississippi and South Carolina resisted the Johnson landslide and
backed Goldwater, the only states outside of Arizona to support him.
   Since then, Southern and border states have voted strongly
Republican except in 1976, when Georgian Jimmy Carter was the
Democratic candidate. In 1980, Reagan took 138 of the region's 169
electoral votes and four years later, the Republican president
received all but the 3 electoral votes of the District of Columbia.
   Democratic pollster Natalie Davis is based in Alabama and she
pointed out that in 1984, Mondale got 13 percent of the white vote
in the state.
   ``If the white vote tripled and the black vote came out the way
it was supposed to, then Dukakis would beat Bush by half a
percentage point,'' she said. ``Think about that as a mission.
We've got to triple what we did in '84.''
   When Claibourne Darden, an Atlanta-based pollster, was asked how
Dukakis was playing in the South, he replied, ``He doesn't play so
hot. He is your classical, party activist, Democratic candidate for
president of which we've seen many come and all go.''
   There was little agreement on whether Texas or Florida would
offer the best hope for a Dukakis breakthrough.
   Texas is where Bush makes his home, where he first became active
in politics and where he was elected to a House seat.
   A Texas Democrat, who insisted on anonymity, called it ``highly
unlikely'' that Dukakis could carry the state, ``as unlikely that
Reagan would carry Minnesota in '84.''
   Jim Quackenbush, who was southern coordinator for the Mondale
campaign, said he thought Dukakis had a better chance of carrying
Texas than of winning Florida.
   ``Florida is just a hard state for a Democrat to take,'' he said.
   Florida Democrats talked optimistically about Dukakis' prospects
against Bush in their state.
   ``The decision on the vice presidency will be fundamental,''
said Wayne Bailey, a professor of political science at Stetson
University in Deland, Fla., and a Democratic Party activist.
   If Dukakis chooses Sen. Sam Nunn of Georgia or Sen. Bob Graham
of Florida, said Bailey, ``The ticket will be very saleable in
Florida.''
   Richard Pettigrew, former Democratic chairman in Dade County,
Fla., said Nunn or Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee or Sen. John
Glenn of Ohio would be the strongest running mates for Dukakis
because they would ``assure people'' on foreign and defense policy.
   Pettigrew and Quackenbush said Nunn would be a lot more
effective in the South than Graham.
   Sabato took the opposite view. He said Nunn might not get
Dukakis any state other than Georgia. While the senator could add a
couple of points to the ticket in other Southern states, it might
not be enough to carry any of them.
   ``Graham would make much more sense,'' he said, because the
senator could bring home Florida for the Democrats.
   Even a partisan like Quackenbush conceded that in the South ``if
you're from Massachusetts, whether it's reality or perception,
you're perceived as a liberal.''
   But he contended that Dukakis can win support in the South by
emphasizing the idea that as a governor he has been ``a fiscal
conservative.''
   A big plus for Dukakis in the South is the perception that Bush
does not have the hold on voters that Reagan had.
   ``Bush's hold on Southern voters is not intense,'' said Sabato.
   ``Nobody gets excited about George Bush,'' said Davis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
