<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1130EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Fiji     05-14 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fiji,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fiji's Marks First Anniversary Of Coup, Police Detain 18 People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUVA, Fiji (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Saturday detained 18 people
demonstrating against the government of Sitiveni Rabuka as Fiji
marked the first anniversary of a military takeover that catapulted
Rabuka to power.
   Rabuka celebrated his first year in power by attending an army
parade where he exhorted soldiers to be considerate in preserving
order this weekend.
   Troops remained on full alert as a precaution against possible
violence, but no major trouble was reported.
   Police broke up a ``demonstration for democracy'' in downtown
Suva while Rabuka attended the parade at the Queen Elizabeth
Barracks army headquarters. He told his troops to be mindful that
some sections of the community had suffered as a result of the coup.
   The celebrations should not ``make things worse for people who
might fear for their safety and their property,'' said Rabuka, in
an apparent reference to Indians, who outnumber ethnic Fijians in
the 715,000 population.
   On May 14, 1987, Rabuka, then a lieutenant colonel and third in
the army's chain of command, led 10 masked soldiers into Parliament
and arrested the elected Indian-majority coalition government of
Prime Minister Timoci Bavadra.
   Rabuka said he staged the coup to protect the interests of
ethnic Fijians, who comprise 47 percent of the population. Bavadra
had been in office only a month after defeating Prime Minister Ratu
Sir Kamisese Mara in April elections.
   After the coup, an interim government was set up, but when it
didn't please Rabuka, he staged a second takeover on Sept. 25.
   Since then a nervous calm has settled over Fiji. The country's
tourist-based economy is in shambles.
   Gross domestic product is down 11 percent, sugar production _
the country's major cash crop _ is down 20.3 percent, tourism has
plummeted 26.9 percent and the Fiji dollar has been devalued by 33
percent.
   At his home in Viseisei, Western Fiji, Bavadra issued a
statement vowing to continue to push for racial equality in Fiji, a
group of 300 islands east of Australia.
   At the parade, Rabuka presented good conduct and meritorious
service medals to six high-ranking army officers, several of whom
were involved in the May 14, 1987 takeover.
   He told supporters that the recipients of the medals were
``shining examples'' to follow.
   Among the demonstrators were members of the Fiji Women's Rights
Organization and a Catholic priest. The women, wearing black as a
sign of mourning, carried placards denouncing the coup.
   Banners reading ``Only One Race _ The Human Race'' and
``Democracy Lives'' were torn down by police, who told the crowd to
leave before it got out of control.
   When they refused to move, police herded some people into vans
and took them away. Officials said the demonstrators were not
charged and would be released later.
   Other demonstrators went to St. Andrew's Presbysterian Church
where, watched from outside by police and soldiers, they held a
religious service.
   On Saturday, the gates at the Parliament building remained
locked. Fiji has had no Parliament since the coup and is now
governed by an interim administration led by Mara while a new
constitution is being written to guarantee power for ethnic Fijians.
   No other incidents were reported and the army was not much in
evidence around the country except for guards at key points, such
as power installations.
</TEXT>
