<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SkyscraperFire     05-14 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Skyscraper Fire,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Chief Seeks Criminal Investigation of Security Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city's fire chief says he will seek a
criminal investigation into an alleged delay by security guards in
reporting a fire that ravaged the state's tallest skyscraper.
   Fire Chief Don Manning said Friday he intends to pursue legal
action ``to the extent possible'' in the wake of the May 4 inferno
that devastated four floors of the First Interstate Bank tower and
left one man dead.
   Security personnel allegedly ``failed to notify the Fire
Department of the fire in a timely manner, which is a violation of
the Los Angeles Municipal Code,'' said Battalion Chief Dean Cathey.
   City officials said security guards reset fire alarms that went
off on the 12th floor because they believed them to be false. They
say guards delayed notifying authorities for seven minutes,
allowing the blaze to spread through the 12th floor of the 62-floor
office building.
   Jim Clauson, an official with Pedus Security Services, Inc., has
disputed fire officials' version of events. Clauson said Pedus
guards called the fire department about a minute after the alarms
went off.
   Fire officials said that when fire alarms sounded a third time
on the 12th floor, security officers sent a building engineer to
the 12th floor to investigate. The worker, Alex Handy, 24, died in
the blaze.
   Manning spoke Friday during state senate hearings currently
being conducted in Los Angeles on proposed fire-sprinkler
legislation. A bill would require the installation of fire
sprinklers in all high-rise buildings in California.
   Clauson did not return telephone seeking comment about the
investigation ordered by Manning.
</TEXT>
