<HEAD>Senate Candidate Returns Hayden Donation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmits a0550 to fix cycle designator</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lt. Gov. Richard A. Licht, running for
the U.S. Senate seat held by John H. Chafee, said he will return a
$250 contribution from former anti-Vietnam war activist Tom Hayden
because of pressure from veterans.
   ``I've spoken with a number of friends of mine who are veterans.
They're very concerned about it. They're very supportive of me, and
they've asked me to return the money, and we will,'' Licht said
Friday during taping of WJAR-TV's ``10 News Conference,'' scheduled
to air Sunday.
   Licht, a Democrat, said he personally has no problem with
Hayden, a California state legislator, and agrees with Hayden on
many issues.
   ``I disagree with some of the things he did 20 years ago,''
Licht said. Licht said Hayden and his wife Jane Fonda have
``apologized for what they did 20 years ago,'' and ``their tactics
were wrong.''
   Licht said he wants to avoid giving Chafee an issue to exploit.
   Chafee spokesman Andy McLeod said the Republican had not made
the Hayden donation an issue, but added that Licht's move was an
admission of ``shame'' for accepting the donation to begin with.
   Bill Shultz, a Hayden spokesman, said he had no comment on the
dispute.
