<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1209EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush'sWeek Bjt   05-14 0884</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush's Week, Bjt,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Week Promising Roses for Republican Candidate Bush Turns Thorny</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was a week that should have come up all
roses for George Bush, with endorsements arriving from both the
president and his only remaining Republican rival. But instead,
thorns littered the way.
   In recent days, Bush and his lieutenants have been forced to
take the defensive on a host of issues, ranging from alleged drug
trafficking by Panamanian leader Manuel Antonio Noriega to a
lackluster endorsement from President Reagan.
   Some of the troubles were minor irritants; others loomed as
potential major problems as the vice president sought to translate
his lock on the Republican presidential nomination into a fall
general election strategy.
   Some of the recent problems besetting the Bush campaign:
   _He unintentionally handed Jesse Jackson a new issue with his
characterization of the Democrat as ``the hustler from Chicago'' in
a speech to a GOP audience in Nebraska. Jackson seized upon the
remark, saying it was offensive and showed Bush had ``started to
panic.''
   _Despite enjoying a mathematical lock on the GOP nomination
since the April 26 Pennsylvania primary, Bush won only 71 percent
of the vote in last Tuesday's Nebraska primary.
   Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., who had withdrawn from the race but whose
name appeared on the ballot, captured 24 percent while Pat
Robertson _ who endorsed Bush the following day to effectively end
his own candidacy _ polled 5 percent.
   _Questions intensified about Bush's prior knowledge of alleged
drug trafficking by Noriega, fueled by news accounts suggesting
that Bush might have known more about the situation than he has
professed.
   The political problems for Bush grew even larger with mid-week
reports suggesting the Reagan administration was considering
dropping U.S. drug charges against the Panamanian general in
exchange for his leaving power.
   Bush, who stresses a resume laden with foreign policy experience
and vows a strong anti-drug effort, again found himself in the
position of having to plead ignorance on Noriega.
   _Fallout from the legal difficulties surrounding Attorney
General Edwin Meese III continued to swirl about the Bush campaign,
heightened by on-the-record assertions by two top Bush advisers
that Meese had become a campaign liability. Bush called the
statements unauthorized. Analysts said the Meese affair could hurt
Bush with voters.
   _And finally, after weeks of jockeying between Bush aides and
the White House over the timing of President Reagan's formal
endorsment of his vice president, Reagan finally delivered _ but
with a terse statement that neither praised Bush nor touched on why
Americans should vote for him.
   Furthermore, Reagan mispronounced Bush's name at one point,
calling him, ``George Bosh.''
   By week's end, the president's mystifyingly brief endorsement
appeared to be the least of the Bush campaign's worries. Bush
declared he ``couldn't be more pleased'' with the chief executive's
manner of support and presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said
Reagan was ``mortified'' to think that his words had been received
as anything less than enthusiastic.
   The campaign showed greater concern over the results of the
Nebraska primary, which showed that Bush could not win solid GOP
support in the state even while running virtually unopposed.
   Political analysts suggested the weak showing underscores a
problem Bush is likely to have in November throughout the Midwest,
where the farm economy, despite some recent signs of improvement,
is still troubled.
   Bush's track record in the region has not been good. Although he
later went on to win commanding victories in other states, he came
in a disappointing third in the Iowa caucuses last February.
   He also lost to Dole in South Dakota's primary, garnering only
19 percent to Dole's 55 percent. And, in Minnesota, Bush didn't
even bother to mount a major effort. A straw poll there in February
showed only 11 percent for Bush, compared to 43 percent for Dole
and 28 percent for Robertson.
   Bush campaign strategists argued that the vice president's poor
showings in the Midwest reflect Kansan Dole's popularity more than
their candidate's vulnerability.
   ``Dole is still very popular (in Nebraska), and there was a very
low turnout,'' said Bush deputy campaign manager Ed Rogers. ``And
we'll take 71 percent of the vote any day of the week.''
   Equally troubling to Bush's general-election prospects,
according to analysts, was new survey evidence suggesting that
Reagan's popularity across party lines was unlikley to be
transferred to his vice president.
   ``No president's popularity is,'' Rogers said. ``What's
important is we're going to have the president as a great resource.
The president packs a lot of wallop out on the stump and everybody
knows it.''
   But David Carmen, a former consultant to New York Rep. Jack
Kemp's presidential campaign, said ``there are problems for Bush
that he's going to have to deal with'' and a lack of ready-made
support among blue-collar Democrats is one of them.
   ``It's a problem he's going to to have to address through
scheduling, speeches and through issues,'' Carmen said.
   To date, said the consultant, ``Bush has had a problem in
articulating a message. He's been slow to do it. But people want a
horse race and there are more Democrats than Republicans in the
country. So it is nautral that the race is going to start out at
least close, or maybe with (Democrat Michael) Dukakis ahead.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
