<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1339EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Gulf     05-14 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Gulf,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Says Attacked Ships Ineligible for Distress Help</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ships and crewmen attacked by Iraq
Saturday were ineligible for U.S. distress assistance under the
Reagan administration's rules of engagement in the Persian Gulf, a
State Department spokeswoman said.
   ``The supertankers were inside one of the exclusion zones, which
both belligerents have declared and they were servicing the port of
a belligerent,'' spokeswoman Sondra McCarty said. ``Each of these
factors disqualifies shipping from U.S. distress assistance.''
   U.S. warships are now permitted to intervene on request in
attacks on neutral shipping as well as to provide ``humanitarian
aid'' to non-U.S. flagged vessels, but only in international waters.
   Today's attack occurred in Iranian waters, at the Larak oil
depot, the latest target in Iraq's intensified attempt to strangle
petroleum exports that help Tehran finance the war.
   McCarty repeated U.S. assertions that ``there can be no military
solution the war,'' and that any fighting that prolongs the
conflict is regrettable.
   She pleaded anew for U.N. Security Council action to implement a
10-month old resolution calling for a truce in the conflict and an
arms embargo against belligerents who fail to heed the cease-fire
call.
   The Soviet Union and China have declined to endorse the
resolution, asserting that diplomatic efforts toward a truce have
not been exhausted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
