<DOCNO> AP880514-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1349EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     05-14 0937</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0973</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ailing funny lady Lucille Ball is feeling
better, but will have to stay in Cedars-Sinai Medical Center at
least until Monday, a hospital spokeswoman said Saturday.
   Spokeswoman Paula Correia said doctors decided late Friday they
wanted the comedian to stay for tests and observation.
   ``Everything seems to be OK, but they just want to be sure,''
Ms. Correia said.
   Miss Ball, 76, the zany redhead of television's ``I Love Lucy,''
became ill at home Wednesday and checked herself in.
   Hospital spokesman Ron Wise said Friday that although doctors
were still unable to diagnose the cause of Miss Ball's illness, she
apparently does not have cardiac trouble, as originally feared.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $1.3 million-suit by two teen-agers who
claim they were hurt by flying dry ice during a concert by the
heavy metal rock band Motley Crue is expected to go to a jury
Monday.
   Special effects expert Dave Pier testified Friday that there was
no explosion at the 1985 concert that could have blasted dry ice
into the audience.
   Defendants in the civil suit include Motley Crue, concert
promoter Sound Seventy Productions Inc. of Nashville, Tenn., and
the city of Huntsville.
   David Wright, now 19, claims he suffered a facial cut at the
1985 concert in Huntsville from a piece of dry ice hurled into the
audience during a pyrotechnic display.
   Robbie Miller, now 17, says he was permanently blinded in one
eye during the display.
   The trial was recessed for the weekend and jury deliberations
are expected to begin after rebuttal testimony and closing
arguments.
   Pier demonstrated the band's pyrotechnics Friday by heating a
large hunk of dry ice with a torch. There was a whining noise but
no explosion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop Desmond Tutu, seeking scholarships for
students from his troubled South Africa, said he will return any
honorary degrees from U.S. schools that fail to divest their South
African holdings within a year.
   ``I want to give notice here,'' Tutu said Friday during a speech
at Northeastern University, where he was given an honorary
doctorate of divinity.
   The Anglican prelate, who won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1984 for
his non-violent opposition to apartheid, said his gesture may be
small, but is necessary to preserve his integrity.
   Tutu, who received an honorary degree from Harvard University in
1979, did not mention Harvard in his speech. However, he told a
group of reporters and editors of The Boston Globe on Thursday that
his reaction to Harvard's continuing refusal to divest would be:
``Sorry. Have back your degree for the sake of our people.''
   At a reception prior to a $1,000-a-plate fund-raising dinner
Friday night, Tutu urged people to donate to his scholarship fund
as a means of striking a blow against apartheid.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BECKLEY, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. John Cannell, who uncovered the
so-called ``Lake Wobegon'' effect on standarized tests that falsely
reassures educators their students are ``above average,'' says he's
leaving West Virginia.
   Cannell on Friday said he has sold his share in a medical clinic
and is moving in June to study psychiatry at the University of New
Mexico.
   Cannell said his involvement in education helped lead to his
decision to switch from general medicine to adolescent psychiatry.
   ``I've become convinced that many of the problems of adolescents
can be blamed on the school system,'' Cannell said. ``Not all of
them, but a good part, go back to the message of failure that the
school systems give.''
   For years, Cannell claimed that West Virginia's Education
Department exaggerated its accomplishments by trumpeting results of
the McGraw-Hill Comprehensive Test of Basic Skills. Every school
district that used the tests claimed results above the national
average.
   Cannell maintains that publishers of such tests deliberately
market them to make school districts look good. McGraw-Hill and
others have denied the allegation.
   In February, after meeting with Cannell and studying his
research, Assistant Education Secretary Chester Finn Jr. said some
so-called achievement tests give ``a falsely optimistic'' picture
of school district performances.
   Finn likened the test results to humorist Garrison Keillor's
mythical town of Lake Wobegon, where ``all the women are strong,
all the men are good-looking and all the children are above
average.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PORT ANGELES, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Short story writer and poet Raymond
Carver will receive an honorary doctorate from the University of
Connecticut on Sunday, the day his new collection of stories,
``Where I'm Calling From,'' is released.
   Carver will also be inducted into the American Academy and
Institute of Arts and Letters in New York on Wednesday, said his
longtime companion, poet and short story writer Tess Gallagher. The
couple lives near here.
   Last year both received a Governor's Writers Award from Gov.
Booth Gardner. Carver was honored for ``Ultramarine,'' his first
volume of poetry, and Ms. Gallagher won for ``A Lover of Horses,''
her first collection of short stories.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: Hobert is cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bluegrass pioneer Bill Monroe recorded
his latest album in coal country, but it took another country
star's father to come up with a name for one of the tracks.
   When he heard it, Hobert Skaggs dubbed the upbeat instrumental
``Stone Coal.'' It appears on Monroe's new LP, ``Southern Flavor.''
   ``I put that together up in the eastern part of Kentucky,''
Monroe, 75, said. ``Ricky Skaggs and his father were there and his
father came up with that name, `Stone Coal.' ''
   Monroe, ``the father of bluegrass music,'' has been making
records since the 1930s. Ricky Skaggs is known for hits such as
``Country Boy'' and ``Heartbroke.''
