<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Trade     05-14 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Trade,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Poised to Veto Trade Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Saturday that while
workers should get as much warning as possible before they're fired
or laid off, he cannot sign a trade bill requiring such
notification because it ``threatens to destroy jobs.''
   ``It is unfortunate, but I have no choice but to send this back
to Congress,'' Reagan said of the 1,000-page trade measure. White
House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the veto would occur in the
coming week.
   In his weekly radio address, delivered from Camp David, Md.,
Reagan zeroed in on the battle over the plant-closing section of
the bill, which is expected to become a campaign issue in the fall
elections.
   While the administration supports much of the bill, it faults
the requirement that companies notify workers at least 60 days in
advance of layoffs or a plant shutdown.
   The issue should be decided between labor and management, not
government, Reagan argued.
   ``Let me state very clearly, I believe businesses should give
workers and communities just as much warning as they can when it
looks as though layoffs or plant closings are going to become
unavoidable,'' Reagan said. ``It's the humane thing to do.''
   ``But when big government gets in the middle of something like
this, dictating all its rules and regulations, the humane way has a
way of becoming inhumane,'' Reagan said.
   The president contended that the requirement would force
struggling businesses to shut down at crucial times, and that
management needs the flexibility of using temporary layoffs to get
a business back on its feet. It would also keep companies from
adding workers if it would subject them to the bill's requirements,
the president said.
   Although there are exceptions in the bill for companies that
find themselves in serious financial trouble, but Reagan derided
them as ``too vague and unclear to be workable.''
   Reagan argued that ``one independent study'' showed that if the
plant-closing provision had been in effect from 1982 to 1986,
``America would have almost half a million fewer jobs.'' He did not
cite the source of the study.
   In the Democratic response, House Speaker Jim Wright said the
nation needs the bill to combat the worst trade deficit in history
_ $171 billion. ``It weakens our country, depresses wages, reduces
our standard of living,'' Wright argued.
   He took issue with Reagan's threat to veto the bill over the
plant closing provision.
   ``This bill simply ... asks the nation's biggest employers to
give American workers at least 60 days' notice before they close
another plant. That's not too much to ask. Not sufficient cause,
Mr. President, to abandon the work of three years and scrap this
vitally needed legislation,'' Wright said.
   The House speaker contended that ``86 percent of the American
people support this plant closing provision.''
   ``Top management knows in advance when its service is no longer
required and builds golden parachutes worth millions of dollars for
its comfort. Can't we give the workers of America at least 60 days
to get their lives in order, to get new training, to cushion the
blow?'' Wright asked.
   Democrats sent the bill to the White House last week with a
parade of razzle-dazzle events and photo sessions, and have
threatened to hit Republicans in the fall with the issue if Reagan
vetoes the measure.
   The bill would overhaul the system for imposing import curbs to
retaliate against international trade violations and aid American
industries threatened by increased foreign competition.
   While it cleared the House by a 312-107 margin _ more than the
two-thirds needed to override a presidential veto _ it was approved
in the Senate by 63-36, three votes shy of the margin sufficient to
override.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880514-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1357EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Democrats-Text     05-14 0663</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats-Text,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan-Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of the Democratic response to
President Reagan's weekly radio address. It was delivered Saturday
by House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas.
   Good afternoon. This is Jim Wright. Let's talk a little bit
together about the most important thing to come out of Congress
this year.
   The new trade bill we sent to the president this week can be a
big victory for America. It can help us get back on track to being
No. 1 in the world.
   Last year, our country suffered the worst trade deficit in our
history _ $171 billion. We paid that much more for foreign goods
than we sold in American-made products. And that can be devastating.
   It weakens our country, depresses wages, reduces our standard of
living. In all, the trade deficit cost the average American family
about $3,000 last year.
   Because of this, we're no longer No. 1 in per capita gross
national product. Last year we fell to No. 3.
   Because of these trade deficits, our country, which was the No.
1 creditor nation in the world just five years ago, is the world's
largest debtor nation today. And foreign ownership of American
banks, American farms and real estate, and America's marketable
securities increases by about 25 percent each year.
   America can do better than that. We must do better than that.
The new trade bill will put us on an upward path. Its contents are
summed up in three important words _ rules, tools and schools.
   New rules to make a level playing field, to give American
products a chance on foreign markets. We ask other countries to
treat our goods just as we treat their goods on our markets _ no
better, no worse.
   New tools to strengthen our industrial base, to modernize our
plants, to improve our American productivity.
   Better schools to prepare America's children for increasing
world competition and to hone and sharpen the skills of America's
work force.
   America needs this bill. And so we plead with President Reagan:
Please sign the trade bill. Give America a chance to excel on world
markets again. Let ``Made in the USA'' become a badge of quality
and value throughout the world.
   President Reagan has threatened to veto this bill simply because
it asks the nation's biggest employers to give American workers at
least 60 days' notice before they close another plant. That's not
too much to ask. Not sufficient cause, Mr. President, to abandon
the work of three years and scrap this vitally needed legislation.
   Eighty-six percent of the American people support this plant
closing provision, this notification to workers. They say it's only
fair.
   Top management knows in advance when its service is no longer
required and builds golden parachutes worth millions of dollars for
its comfort. Can't we give the workers of America at least 60 days
to get their lives in order, to get new training, to cushion the
blow?
   In the name of the 2 million American workers who lost their
jobs last year because of plant shutdowns and layoffs _ many of
those plants going overseas, two-thirds of them given no notice at
all _ Mr. President, we ask you to sign this bill and let it become
law.
   In the name of Patsy Edwards and 117 employees who lost their
jobs in Tampa (Fla.) with only one day notice, please sign the
trade bill.
   In the name of Hank Schrenko and 160 iron workers at a plant in
Syracuse (N.Y.) which closed with only 15 minutes' notice, please
sign this bill, Mr. President.
   In the name of Wally Barrett and 397 workers who lost their jobs
at a plant in Eau Claire, Wis., please sign the bill.
   In the name of these and others in America's work force, good
Americans who want to help us revive this country, we call on you,
Mr. President, to consider the equities and let this vital American
initiative begin.
</TEXT>
