<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan-Guerrillas     05-14 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan-Guerrillas,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Guerrilla Leader Offers Limited Amnesty For Communist
Troops</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-communist insurgents Saturday
offered limited amnesty to Afghan government soldiers as Soviet
troops prepared for the start of their withdrawal from Afghanistan.
   Gulbadin Hekmatyar, chairman of the seven-party Afghan guerrilla
alliance, said Afghan security forces who voluntarily surrender
within four weeks after Soviet troops have left their districts
would not be tried for war crimes.
   ``Once captured ... they will face Islamic courts,'' Hekmatyar
said at a news conference at the alliance's Peshawar headquarters.
   He did not say what punishments they would face if convicted.
   The insurgents have vowed to continue and intensify their fight
until the last of the estimated 115,000 Soviet troops leave
Afghanistan and the Marxist government in Kabul falls.
   Hekmatyar said the rebels had postponed a swap of one Soviet
prisoner for 25 captured guerrillas. He said his group will keep
Soviet prisoners until it establishes an Islamic government in
Afghanistan.
   He did not divulge how many Soviet or Afghan army troops were
being held.
   The leader of the extremist Hezb-E-Islami Party said his party
will hold onto Soviet prisoners and try to exchange them for
Afghanistan President Najib and other high-ranking members of the
ruling People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan.
   He said the guerrillas want to put Najib and his associates on
trial for war crimes.
   Western observers disagree on how long Najib can stay in power
once his 100,000-strong security force is left to face the
guerrillas alone.
   The rebels claim to have overrun 50 posts and garrisons, mostly
in eastern Afghanistan, in the last month as Red Army troops have
headed toward Kabul in preparation for their withdrawal, which
begins Sunday.
   ``May 15 means the defeat of Soviet forces militarily in
Afghanistan and the start of the puppet regime's collapse,'' said
Hekmatyar. ``The Russian withdrawal is the first phase of our
victory.''
   ``May 15 also proves that in wars, modern weapons and number of
troops do not matter,'' he said, adding, ``no power, however
arrogant, is able to crush a nation committed to its faith.''
   Hekmatyar said the guerrillas would be willing to talk to United
Nations advisers, who will oversee the nine-month Soviet troop
withdrawal.
   The 50-man force, headed by Gen. Rauli Helminen of Finland, is
composed of military personnel mainly from European countries and
Canada.
   The U.N. Good Offices Mission for Afghanistan and Pakistan said
that starting Sunday the group will inspect Soviet, Afghan and
guerrilla military bases in Afghanistan and refugee camps in
Pakistan.
   The guerrilla alliance, composed of four Moslem extremist groups
and three moderate traditionalist parties, has begun forming its
own alternative government.
   Hekmatyar said the new Islamic-style government will establish
itself inside Afghanistan in the near future. He has given no date.
   Najib's party seized power in a bloody 1978 coup. Soviet troops
intervened in December 1979, replacing one pro-Moscow government
with another.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
