<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--ElderlyHomicide     05-14 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Elderly Homicide,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Elderly Man Charged In Nursing Home Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elderly man has been charged with killing a
fellow nursing home resident by striking him with a cane during an
argument over an ashtray, police said.
   Adolph Rentell, 86, was arrested and charged with criminal
homicide Friday at St. Francis Hospital, where he has been a
patient for a week.
   He was arraigned in the hospital but will remain hospitalized
indefinitely for psychiatric evaluation, according to city homicide
detectives.
   Rentell is charged in the death of Jack Vassanelli, 87.
Vassanelli died last Sunday, two days after he was attacked in a
hallway of Negley House, a nursing home.
   An autopsy showed Vassanelli died of meningitis, a complication
from infection and broken facial bones caused by blows to his face.
   The attack came after Vassanelli, who was in a wheelchair, asked
Rentell to stop spitting into an ashtray Vassanelli was using,
police said.
   Despite Rentell's age and questions about his mental state,
police say he was charged because they believe he was aware of his
actions at the time of the attack.
