<DOCNO> AP880514-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1415EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0557 05-14 0947</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Afghanistan, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0557,0967</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Pullout: The Beginning of the End of Soviet Military Role</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `On Saturday...' to ADD rocket blast; SUBS
14th graf, ``We consider ...,' with 2 grafs to UPDATE with
guerrillas offering limited amnesty to Afghan troops. PICKS up 15th
graf, `Gromov, who ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos KAB3, KAB1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bloodied but unbroken, the Soviet Army begins
pulling out of Afghanistan on Sunday amid threats of guerrilla
harassment and grave doubts about the future of the Marxist
government it leaves behind.
   On the eve of the withdrawal, the Soviet commander in
Afghanistan denied his men had been defeated in the brutal war that
has claimed an estimated 10,000 Soviet lives.
   But politically, the fruits of the 8{-year Soviet armed
intervention seem meager. Militarily, the Soviet presence has
proved far from decisive.
   On Saturday, in the Afghan capital of Kabul, a bomb exploded
inside a truck near reviewing stands built for a ceremony honoring
the departing Soviet troops. Eleven Afghan civilians were reported
killed. Later, three rockets hit a village outside Kabul, killing
four people.
   Since Dec. 27, 1979, when the Kremlin sent tanks and troops into
Afghanistan, Soviet soldiers have been fighting to prop up the
People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan, but they have failed to
break the back of a nationwide anti-Marxist insurgency.
   Acknowledging the Kremlin's unwillingness to keep bearing the
military and diplomatic costs of the intervention, Foreign Minister
Eduard A. Shevardnadze signed U.N.-brokered accords in Geneva on
April 14 that commit the Soviets to a nine-month pullout, beginning
Sunday.
   As the first of an estimated 115,000 Soviet troops prepare to
come home, one major question is how _ or if _ the Moscow-aligned
regime of President Najib, which claims just 40,000 regular
soldiers of its own, can survive.
   The first Soviets to leave will be from a motor-rifle division
garrisoned at Jalalabad, a dusty provincial town 30 miles from the
Pakistan border, military officials and Soviet media have said.
   Lt. Gen. Boris V. Gromov, Soviet commander in Afghanistan, said
Saturday more than 1,000 soldiers would leave Jalalabad on Sunday
and that a quarter of the entire Soviet contingent would be home by
the time President Reagan visits Moscow on May 29-June 2.
   In recent days, Soviet media have issued alarming reports about
increasing guerrilla activity, perhaps to ready public opinion for
losses during the withdrawal, or to stress that the pullout will
heighten the likelihood of bloodshed among the Afghan factions
locked in a 10-year-old civil war.
   Soviet television took its viewers Thursday to the
Kabul-Kandahar-Herat road, a 650-mile crescent-shaped track that
links three of Afghanistan's major cities, for a taped interview
with a Red Army officer assigned to screen the pullout.
   ``The activity of armed opposition bands has been sharply
increasing,'' said Lt. Col. N.V. Ivanov, who spoke as a truck
convoy crawled along the hilly road in back of him. ``The road will
apparently become an objective for which they will fight till the
bitter end.''
   Guerrilla commanders, who refused to be party to the Geneva
agreements, have vowed to give the Soviets no respite during the
pullout.
   Gulbaddin Hekmatyar, head of the seven-party rebel alliance,
offered a limited amnesty to Afghan forces who surrender within
four weeks after Soviet troops leave their districts.
   He said Saturday in Pakistan that those who surrendered in time
would not be tried for war crimes. But he said those who don't
surrender and are captured will face Islamic courts.
   Gromov, who spoke at a news conference in Kabul, said the rebels
had recently received antitank weapons, but warned: ``If any group
tries to use any weapons, retribution will be quick and severe.''
   Asked if the pullout was a defeat, the 44-year-old commander
said: ``The Soviet Army will return home after fulfilling its
internationalist duty ... During the war, not a single unit
retreated in the face of the enemy, so we cannot speak of a
military defeat.''
   Gromov's remarks were made available to The Associated Press in
a pool report from the British news agency Reuters. The AP was
excluded from the pool because of questions it asked Najib in the
Afghan capital last month.
   Most of the Soviets will be traveling by land, rather than by
airlift. For some convoys, the trek to Soviet border cities like
Termez and Kushka is expected to take three days or more, often
through rugged, mountainous terrain where the rebels have been
active in the past.
   Air cover for the retreating columns may be a crucial problem,
as the insurgents have U.S.-made Stinger missiles, deadly against
low-flying helicopters and planes.
   Fearing the heat-seating Stinger, the Soviets and Afghans in
1986 virtually ceased using their aircraft for ground support
missions.
   As they withdraw, the Soviets will hand over more than 170
military bases with equipment worth $1 billion to their Afghan
allies, Gromov said.
   Najib, 41, a burly, mustachioed Marxist who is a former head of
the Afghan secret police, has scoffed when asked whether the
departure of his Soviet allies will bring about the downfall of his
government.
   However, many of the dozens of posts handed over to his army in
recent weeks reportedly have been overrun by well-armed guerrillas.
   Soviet media reports have said Soviet soldiers believe they have
honorably performed their duty in coming to the support of a
beleagured government, but the media have made no secret of the
men's desire to return home.
   In the television interview, Lt. Col. Ivanov, whose detachment
will protect other units as they withdraw, pointed to his men and
said: ``They say we will certainly envy the first columns that go
home.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
