<DOCNO> AP880514-0106 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1422EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BusinessLeaders     05-14 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Business Leaders,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Senate Leaders See Good Chance for Shrinking Budget Deficit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOT SPRINGS, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican leaders in the Senate
reassured the nation's top business executives Saturday that the
outlook is good for shrinking the federal budget deficit.
   The Business Council, composed of 61 chief executives of the
nation's largest corporations, heard from Sen. Pete V. Domenici,
R-N.M., and Sen. Alan K. Simpson, R-Wyo., as the group wrapped up a
two-day conference.
   The sessions of the elite council are private, but Domenici told
reporters before speaking to the executives, ``I'm not one of those
who is going to go before this business group and predict gloom and
fear.''
   Domenici is ranking Republican on the Senate Budget Committee
and a member of a national bipartisan commission that began meeting
last week to devise ways to lower the deficit.
   The business executives, as they opened their twice-a-year
conference at The Homestead, a plush resort in the mountains of
southwestern Virginia, issued a generally upbeat assessment of the
nation's economic prospects this year, but warned that the budget
deficit remains ``disturbingly high'' during such a period of good
times.
   Edmund T. Pratt Jr., chairman of Pfizer Inc., a health care
corporation, said many business leaders enjoying the moderate
economic growth have a sense of ``living on borrowed time'' because
of government red ink.
   ``I think most of us still regard the budget deficit as the No.
1 problem facing us,'' said Robert J. Kilpatrick, chairman of CIGNA
Corp., an insurance company.
   The executives, in a forecast representing a consensus of member
corporation's chief economists, said that the budget deficit would
rise from $150.2 billion last year to $154 billion both this year
and in 1989. The Congressional Budget Office estimates the deficit
will be $157 billion in 1988.
   But Domenici said ``we've made significant strides'' and
predicted the government would ``very easily'' meet the $136
billion, 1989 target of the Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction law.
   He said he did not want to prematurely divulge the positions he
will be taking in the deliberations of the national commission.
   But, he said, ``I don't think it's as simple, as some are
saying, that we ought to just look out there for some big tax, just
so it's not income or corporate income tax.''
   ``We better be guarded about taxes with the American economy
doing as well as it is,'' he said.
   Simpson, who is deputy Republican leader in the Senate, spoke to
the executives Friday night.
   He told reporters Saturday that the government must limit the
growth of federal entitlement programs to achieve any meaningful
reduction in the deficit.
   ``When we deal honestly with Medicare, Social Security,
veteran's benefits, then we'll get something done. All else is
dancing in the night,' he said.
   He said he believed the national commission would propose a
sensible package because the co-chairmen, former Transportation
Secretary Drew Lewis and Washington lawyer Robert Strauss, ``are
pretty gutsy guys.''
   On another matter, Simpson said he was optimistic that Congress,
despite a tight schedule, will pass a second and better trade bill
after President Reagan vetoes the bill sent to him last week.
   Simpson said two key Democratic leaders, House Speaker Jim
Wright, D-Texas, and Senate Finance Committee Chairman Lloyd
Bentsen, D-Texas, were unlikely to let the legislation die because
of strong support in their home state for repeal of the windfall
profits tax on oil, which is included in the massive trade bill.
   The president is expected to reject the legislation because of a
provision that would require companies to give 60 days notice of
plant closings and major layoffs.
   U.S. Trade Representative Clayton K. Yeutter, who went before
the business group on Friday, said the plant closing provision was
``onerous'' because it would provide a legal basis for challenging
virtually every closing or layoff.
</TEXT>
