<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1459EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Iran-Punishment     05-14 0148</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Iran-Punishment,0153</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Morals Offenders To Be Whipped In Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's Supreme Judicial Council on
Saturday approved a law under which people who offend ``public
morals'' will receive 74 lashes.
   State-run Iranian television, monitored in Cyprus, said the law
would apply to those who take any action ``or pretend to take any
action'' that hurts public morals. It did not spell out the
offenses.
   Under Iran's Islamic government, husbands and wives are
forbidden from kissing or showing physical affection in public.
Such actions are often referred to as offending morality.
   After approval by the council, the law took effect immediately.
The beatings are administered with a metal-cored flexible whip with
an outer covering.
   Men are sometimes beaten in public, women always in private.
   Iran's revolutionary legal code has an elaborate list of
punishments, with precise numbers of lashes given for each category
of offense.
</TEXT>
