<DOCNO> AP880514-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1624EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ethiopia     05-14 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethiopia,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Says It Defeated Rebel Offensive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government troops crushed heavily
armed Eritrean rebels who tried to take a strategic northern town
for the second time in a week, the Ethiopian News Agency said
Saturday.
   The official agency said guerrillas of the Eritrean People's
Liberation Front suffered heavy casualties when they attacked Keren
last Wednesday. It gave no figures and did not mention government
casualties.
   But the rebels claimed Saturday in a clandestine broadcast that
they had put 4,000 soldiers ``out of action'' in a ``heavy
offensive'' in the Keren area. It was not clear whether they were
referring to the same battle.
   There was no way independently to confirm either of the claims.
Ethiopia's government rarely comments on rebel claims and both
sides often exaggerate.
   The Ethiopian News Agency said government troops captured
machine guns, rocket launchers, radio equipment, medicine,
documents and large quantities of ammunition.
   It said a number of houses were destroyed in the battle, but
that normal life had returned to the city 56 miles from Asmara,
capital of Eritrea province.
   Rebels have been entrenched in hills surrounding Keren since
April after a three-month offensive in which they captured several
towns.
   Last Monday, the agency reported soldiers had repulsed another
attack on Keren. It indicated the government has begun a
counteroffensive promised by President Mengistu Haile Mariam on
March 31.
   On that day, Mariam acknoweldged the war for the first time and
said his troops were involved in a ``grim struggle'' against the
Eritrean rebels and the Tigre People's Liberation Front.
   Eritrea and Tigre, Ethiopia's northernmost provinces, are the
worst hit by a drought that threatens the lives of 7 million
people, nearly half of whom are in the war zone.
   Eritrean rebels have been fighting for 27 years in Africa's
longest civil war, and Tigrean rebels took up arms 14 years ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880514-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1622EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Yugoslavia 2ndLd-Writethru a0581 05-14 0651</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0581,0666</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Both Chambers Reject No Confidence Motion, Premier Still In Power</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with parliament rejecting no confidence
measure.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist premier Branko Mikulic on
Saturday survived calls for his resignation from Yugoslavia's most
Westernized republics when the parliament rejected their plan to
topple his government.
   In a 75-minute speech to the Federal Assembly, Yugoslavia's
national parliament, Mikulic denounced Slovenia and Croatia, the
two most advanced of Yugoslavia's six republics, for demanding a
vote of no confidence in his administration.
   The parliament then held separate closed debates in its two
chambers, the Federal Chamber and the Chamber of Republics and
Provinces. Each chamber voted against even calling a vote on the
Slovenian and Croatian proposals for a no-confidence motion, the
Tanjug news agency said.
   If Mikulic had been voted out of office, it would have been the
first such vote against a Communist government anywhere in Eastern
Europe.
   Yugoslav television said the Federal Chamber voted 125 to 64 in
a show of hands against a no-confidence motion. The vote in the
other chamber was 64 to 23, Tanjug said.
   The Federal Chamber has a total of 220 delegates, and the other
chamber 88 deputies. Some deputies were apparently absent from
Saturday's session, while five Federal Chamber members abstained.
   Yugoslavia has been grappling with a prolonged economic and
social crisis that has recently prompted calls for a multi-party
system to replace the Communists' current monopoly on power.
   In his speech, Mikulic suggested alternative political systems
could eventually be debated, noting that ``our situation is so
serious that we have no right to put off a debate on the true
reasons which caused it and on its eradication.''
   For the moment, however, he said there is ``no political
alternative to Socialist self-management,'' the system of worker
management bequeathed by Josip Broz Tito and now widely blamed for
some of the nation's economic woes.
   Sixteen percent of the workforce is unemployed and the foreign
debt exceeds $20 billion. Inflation touched almost 200 percent
before the government slapped a six-month freeze on wages and
prices last November.
   The freeze was to be lifted Sunday night, but the government
announced Wednesday it would stay in force at least 10 more days
while Yugoslavia tries to raise an emergency $300 million loan.
   That money is needed to stave off virtual bankruptcy before a
new agreement with the International Monetary Fund takes effect.
   The IMF has worked with Yugoslav officials for more than six
months to devise a package of market-oriented reforms aimed at
reducing inflation to 90 percent while rescheduling payments on $2
billion of debt and extending $1.4 billion in new loans.
   By backing Mikulic, parliament signaled that it supports the
reforms.
   Mikulic said the new measures would be harsh but warned that
``even greater stagflation'' and drastic reductions in real wages
lay ahead if inflation exceeds the target of 90 percent.
   The premier blamed ``the antiquity, lack of flexibility and
inefficiency'' of Yugoslavia's current economic system for the
crisis.
   He outlined the new economic reforms in general terms, saying
they aimed to curb import restrictions, open up competition with
the world market and strengthen the role of the National Bank in
monetary policy.
   Mikulic said he agreed with his critics that Yugoslavia's
situation was grave but he defended his government's two years in
office so far, noting that each of its acts had been approved by
the national parliament and republican assemblies.
   Several Slovenian and Croatian deputies argued against this in
what Tanjug termed ``an occasionally very sharp and polemical
debate.''
   Joze Marolt, a Slovene delegate, recalled that in July 1986
Mikulic submitted what was then called an emergency economic
package and warned that Yugoslavia stood before an abyss.
   ``Today, we are not just in front of the abyss, we are in it,''
Marolt said, according to Tanjug.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
