<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1623EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-France-Government 1stLd-Writethru a0606 05-14 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Government, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0606,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mitterrand Dissolves Assembly and Calls Election</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 9 grafs with Giscard d'Estaing opposing dissolution.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HARRY DUNPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Francois Mitterrand dissolved the
National Assembly on Saturday and announced that parliamentary
elections will be held June 5 and June 12.
   Mitterrand made the announcement in a nationwide television
address.
   Mitterrand said he made the decision after his new premier,
Michel Rocard, informed him ``that despite his efforts, he did not
believe he could bring together a solid and stable majority that
all governments need to carry out their programs well.''
   Rocard said Friday he had sought support from centrists in the
577-seat Assembly for his government and received a negative
response.
   In his three-minute address, Mitterrand deplored the fact that
``the opening (to the center) that I sought could not be brought
about to the extent that I wished. Therefore, it was my duty to
draw the appropriate conclusions. A few seconds ago I signed a
decree dissolving the National Assembly.''
   He said the two-round election would be held on the first and
second Sundays of June.
   Mitterrand was re-elected to a second term May 8 and appointed
Rocard his premier after conservative Premier Jacques Chirac, who
had run against Mitterrand for president, resigned.
   According to an opinion poll to be published Sunday in the
Journal du Dimanche, 47 percent of the French favored dissolution
of the Assembly, while 28 percent opposed dissolution.
   The poll indicated that the Socialists, the largest party in
France, would get 41 percent of the vote, 24 percent would go to
the neo-Gaullist Rally for the Republic, and 15 percent would go to
the center-right Union for French Democracy.
   The rest of the vote would go to minor parties on the left and
the right, the poll indicated. Nearly 20 percent of those polled
said they would not vote.
   Former President Valery Giscard d'Estaing, a prominent
center-right leader, told Mitterrand earlier he should convene the
Assembly before deciding on dissolution.
   Giscard said in a letter to Mitterrand the action should come
``after a serious discussion on what is possible and what is not.''
   He said he opposed dissolution for two reasons.
   ``The French now will have to vote five times in 15 months'' in
various elections, which Giscard described as ``great waste of time
and energy.''
   He also said that the central problem facing the country was how
to get the left and the right to work together.
   ``How can we achieve this if the first decision, before any
attempt to work together, is to send the two camps face to face
against each other in every electoral district in France.''
   Mitterrand acted six days after winning a second-seven year term
with 54 percent of the vote. He also dissolved the Assembly after
winning his first term in 1981 and was rewarded with a victory by
the Socialists in the legislative elections that followed.
   The last dissolution before that was pronounced by Charles de
Gaulle on May 30, 1968 after the student uprising in Paris.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
