<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1626EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Hungary-Union 1stLd-Writethru   05-14 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Union, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0580,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientists, Educators Form First Independent Union</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with participants saying status of
new union unclear, adds quotes and details. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists, educators and other
intellectuals Saturday formed communist Hungary's first new trade
union in 40 years.
   It was not known whether the Democratic Union of Scientific
Workers would be independent of the government-approved union
structure, said a participant who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``You certainly cannot compare the (union) with the Polish trade
union Solidarity, because it is a non-political organization,'' he
said. Solidarity, the Soviet bloc's first independent union
federation, was banned in 1981.
   The participant said about 400 people attended the founding
session and elected a 59-member steering committee.
   The meeting was to take place at the Science Faculty of
Budapest's Eoetvoes Lorand University, but it had to be shifted to
the Metro Club, a cultural club, because the university rector
withdrew an earlier permit granted by the dean.
   The new union includes representatives of natural, social and
technical sciences, higher education and research institutes. Other
members include laboratory assistants and unemployed researchers.
interests were ignored by the official public employees' union.
Spokesmen said it would fight to improve members' working
conditions, increase funds for research and reduce layoffs.
   ``They intend to campaign for a science policy that consistently
upholds their common interests and for eliminating restrictions
hindering science and education,'' government radio said.
   Participants at the meeting voted to maintain contact with the
official Central Council of Trade Unions. Steering committee member
Csaba Oeri said the union ``is part of the existing Hungarian trade
union movement.''
   But he did not say whether the new union would join the council.
Two council members attended the session but did not address it.
   Gyoergy Kerekes, another steering committee member, said council
president Sandor Gaspar told him it was not hostile to such
initiatives but did not want the meeting to take place.
   Other prominent steering committee members include sociologist
Elemer Hankiss, Julia Szalai, a sociologist and mathematician,
Peter Hanak, one of Hungary's best known historians and Eva Ancsel,
a philosopher and member of the Academy of Sciences.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
