<DOCNO> AP880514-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1636EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Gorshkov     05-14 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Gorshkov,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Admiral Credited With Building Soviet Fleet Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Admiral Sergei Gorshkov, the man credited with
turning the Soviet Union into a modern naval power, has died, the
Soviet news agency Tass said Saturday. He was 78.
   Gorshkov, who was replaced in December 1985 by Vladimir N.
Chernavin, died Friday following a ``severe and prolonged
illness,'' Tass said. It did not specify the cause of death.
   In his 29 years as naval commander, Gorshkov ``showed a talent
of organization and deep knowledge of the naval science,'' Tass
said, quoting an obituary signed by the Central Committee of the
Communist Party, the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet and the Soviet
Council of Ministers.
   ``Gorshkov had a feeling for the new and showed creative
approaches in his work, and in a combat situation he displayed
courage, will and fortitude,'' it said.
   It credited Gorshkov with making a ``big contribution to the
development of the Soviet navy.''
   A Western military attache said at the time of Gorshkov's
retirement that he had been ``an extraordinary naval officer of our
time.''
   The admiral was appointed to head the Soviet navy in 1956 by
Nikita S. Khrushchev, who considered Josef V. Stalin's emphasis on
large surface vessels to be impractical because of their
vulnerability to rocket attacks.
   In a book titled ``Sea Power of the State,'' Gorshkov said the
Soviet navy's development of a fleet of submarines and
missile-launching warships had frustrated ``illusory hopes of
imperialist aggressors that in the sphere of armed conflict at sea
they would have no strong opponent.''
   He also argued that nuclear modernization was as important as
the initial acquisition of nuclear weapons to end the
``unreachability of the American continent.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880514-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1640EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i SouthAfrica-Angola     05-14 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>South Africa-Angola,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa Threatens to Quit Talks Unless Cubans Halt Advance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Saturday
it has threatened to pull out of peace talks with Angola unless the
Angolans' Cuban allies halt a military advance in the war zone.
   South African officials also said Angola should close training
camps of the African National Congress, the main guerrilla group
fighting white-minority rule in South Africa.
   South African and Angolan officials met Friday in Brazzaville,
Congo, and discussed how to resolve Angola's 13-year civil war and
end South African rule over South-West Africa, also known as
Namibia.
   Both sides said the talks produced progress and would lead to
further meetings soon involving the United States and Cuba. All
four countries participated in the initial round of talks May 3-4
in London.
   The South Africa Broadcasting Corp., which adheres closely to
government positions, said that before the talks can resume, Angola
``will have to give assurances that the present southward advance
of the Cuban forces in Angola will be halted.''
   It said Angolan negotiators were told that South Africa ``was
fully informed about the Cuban advance, which apparently was under
the direct command of President Fidel Castro.''
   An estimated 40,000 Cuban troops are in Angola supporting the
Marxist government against the pro-Western Union for the Total
Independence of Angola and its South African allies. Most of the
fighting is in southern Angola.
   The South African Press Association quoted South African
officials as saying the South African delegates ``feared a Cuban
ploy to have a last hard strike in order to make their subsequent
withdrawal diplomatically more palatable.''
   Foreign Minister Roelof ``Pik'' Botha, who led the South African
delegation, ``apparently stressed that if this was the intention
... Angola would pay a heavy price and the Cubans would be severely
punished,'' the press association reported.
   In Lisbon, Portugal, the independent weekly Expresso Saturday
quoted unidentified sources as saying 8,600 Cuban soldiers landed
in Angola by plane and ship in a two-week period at the end of
April and the beginning of May.
   The report said the reinforcements included 2,000 elite Cuban
soldiers known as rangers, a force that previously has not sent
troops to Angola, and 200 helicopter pilots.
   Expresso said the Cubans landed in the Angolan capital, Luanda,
and five other towns without the knowledge or approval of Angolan
authorities, including President Jose Eduardo dos Santos.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880514-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1644EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghan-Bomb 1stLd-Writethru a0566 05-14 0685</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan-Bomb, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0566,0702</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Blast Kills 11, Blamed On Anti-Communist Rebels</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 2-3 with 2 grafs to UPDATE with Tass report on
rocket attack. Pickup 4th graf pvs `Soviet Communist...'; SUBS
grafs 13-17 pvs `Villagers in...last month' with seven grafs to
UPDATE with Tass detail, changes spelling of village to conform
with Tass, and Najib news conference. Pickup 18th graf pvs `Under
an...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb Saturday ripped through a truck
parked near reviewing stands to be used for ceremonies marking the
withdrawal of Soviet troops. Eleven Afghans, including a baby, were
killed.
   Residents said three rockets later hit a village on the
outskirts of Kabul, killing four people and wounding four others.
The official Soviet news agency Tass put the death toll at three.
   Tass, monitored in Moscow, blamed both attacks on Afghan
guerrillas and said one of those responsible for the 5:45 a.m.
truck attack was arrested.
   Soviet Communist Party Central Committee official Vladimir
Sevruk reported that 11 people were killed and 12 injured in the
explosion.
   The blast killed a baby and an 11-year-old girl, and all the
casualties were Afghan civilians, according to a Western
photographer on the scene.
   Most appeared to have been occupants of nearby homes destroyed
by the impact of the explosion, he said.
   ``When the bomb exploded some of the houses nearby just
collapsed,'' said the photographer.
   The blast was so great that it shattered the windows of a bus
depot across the river, 300 yards away and left a crater 20 feet
wide and 10 feet deep.
   Soviet troops arrived afterward, the photographer said by
telephone.
   The blast demolished embankment walls on both sides of the river
that threads through this ancient capital.
   Blood was visible on the gates of a nearby factory and personal
belongings, including carpet slippers, were scattered in the street.
   The bomb had been planted in a large truck that lay badly
mangled at the scene.
   Last month, six people were killed and 49 wounded in another
bomb blast along the river on the 10th anniversary of the April
1978 revolution that brought a Marxist government to power in
Afghanistan and triggered widespread insurrection.
   Tass said the rockets Saturday hit the village of Chamane
Baraqi, killing an old man and two children. Residents said one
rocket hit a hut, killing two children inside and that an elderly
man and another child were killed by debris. The village is located
about a half-mile from the British Embassy.
   At a news conference for foreign journalists who gathered for
the beginning of the Soviet withdrawal, Afghan President Najib said
his government will survive because it offers peace. He added that
he will address the U.N. Special Session on Disarmament in New York
next month and planned trips to Czechoslovakia and Cuba.
   ``We can state confidently that we will last because we strive
and struggle for peace,'' he said. ``Our opponents offer the Afghan
people war, and the people hate this.''
   Also at a news conference Saturday, the head of the Soviet
military contingent in Afghanistan said the anti-Communist rebels
were taking their toll on the Soviet and Afghan troops but that
rebel attacks will not deter the withdrawal, which begins Sunday.
   ``The opposition may have some effect on us, but not much, and
certainly they will not be able to frustrate the timetable,'' Lt.
Gen. Boris Gromov told reporters. ``We have the means at our
disposal to fulfill the timetable.''
   The comments by Gromov and Najib and the report of the rocket
attack were carried in a Reuters news agency pool report from
Kabul. The Associated Press was excluded from the pool because of
questions it asked Afghan President Najib last month.
   Under an accord signed in Geneva on April 14, the Soviets will
complete their withdrawal within nine months. Half of the Soviets
must be out by Aug. 15, according to the peace agreement.
   Soviet soldiers entered the war in December 1979 to help the
allied government fight off the insurgents, and about 115,000
remain here to back forces loyal to President Najib.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
