<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1654EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SharanskyBook     05-14 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sharansky Book,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sharansky Recalls Joke On KGB In New Book</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet dissident Natan Sharansky recalls in a
new book how he forced KGB agents out of his building and into the
cold in Moscow in 1974 by threatening to call the police.
   It is one of the lighter moments in Sharansky's book, ``Fear No
Evil,'' excerpted in the May 23 issue of U.S. News & World Report.
   In the years before his arrest in 1977 on suspicion of passing
secrets to the CIA, Sharansky was a prominent dissident who had
been repeatedly refused permission to emigrate from the Soviet
Union.
   He was often followed by the KGB and says he sometimes found
them a source of amusement. He says ``the most fun'' he had at the
KGB's expense was on Nov. 7, 1974, a Soviet holiday, when Sharansky
had been assigned to work at the Institute for Oil and Gas to take
care of emergencies.
   ``Three tails followed me to work, but because no outsiders were
allowed in our building, they had to remain in the car. A little
later, the security guard called from downstairs to report that a
group of men had come into the lobby to warm up,'' Sharansky said.
   He called the KGB, identified himself and said he was in charge
of the building that day.
   ``Downstairs in the lobby are three KGB men who are following
citizen Sharansky ... did you give them permission to enter?''
There was a long pause, Sharansky said, and the voice asked his
identity.
   ``Sharansky,'' he replied.
   ``You're making fun of us. It's only noon and you're already
drunk!'' the voice said, and hung up.
   Sharansky said he called the building security guard and ordered
him to tell the three men he had spoken to their boss who didn't
approve of their being in the building.
   ``If they don't leave ... I'll notify the police,'' Sharansky
said.
   He said he walked to the window later and saw they were back in
the car.
   ``I always treasured that moment, that wonderful feeling of
having the KGB obey me,'' he writes.
   Sharansky was convicted by a Soviet court in 1978 of being a
spy. He was freed in February 1986 in an East-West prisoner
exchange and joined his wife in Israel.
   The magazine is scheduled to publish additional excerpts in next
week's issue, in which Sharansky details his 90 months in Soviet
prisons and a labor camp.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880514-0132 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1655EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FloraThefts     05-14 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Flora Thefts,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thieves Steal Shrubs from Charleston Gardens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents are blaming a different kind
of garden grub for nipping their spring in the bud.
   Devious defoliators have been stalking the gardens of this city
by night to steal shrubs and trees.
   ``It's just so awful,'' said Barbara Schaeufele, who had five
rhododendrons stolen from her yard on Mother's Day.
   ``I waited four years to get them. You could just croak.''
   ``A person has to be pretty low to steal someone's shrubbery,''
said a residential developer who lost 10 freshly planted dogwood
trees. The trees, worth $150 each, were uprooted on May 2 from a
neighborhood dotted with homes worth about $300,000 to $500,000.
   Burglars also snatched six shrubs from the city's posh South
Hills district on April 21, police said.
   In Spencer, about 35 miles northeast of Charleston, police
arrested a man late last month who allegedly held an elderly man at
gunpoint while two others stole a month-old $385 garden tiller.
   State Police Cpl. R.J. Strobbe said the tiller was taken to
Charleston and sold.
   Charleston residents who have had their plants pilfered believe
they are being sold on the green market also.
   Audra Cooper, Barbara Schaeufeles' neighbor, said her 2-year-old
rhododendron was preparing to bloom when it was stolen on Mother's
Day.
   ``I never heard of them just walking into the yard and digging
up a plant,'' Cooper said. ``I know several other people down the
street lost shrubs, too.''
   The wave of thefts has surprised residents in some of the city's
finer areas, where crime is relatively rare, but police say there
is not much they can do.
   ``It's a crime of opportunity,'' said Sgt. Dallas Staples,
adding that plant larcenies crop up every spring.
   ``It's kind of hard to do anything,'' Staples said. ``Where do
you begin? How do you put identification on a plant?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880514-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1658EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Stark     05-14 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stark,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy To Remember Fallen Stark Crew Members</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAYPORT NAVAL STATION, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives and friends of the
37 sailors who died when the USS Stark was hit by two missiles in
the Persian Gulf will gather here on the first anniversary of the
attack to remember their fallen loved ones.
   A ceremony is scheduled for Tuesday at the Stark Memorial,
located on the dock where the Stark departed in February 1987 for
the routine deployment, and where the burned-out guided missile
frigate returned six months later to a subdued heroes' welcome.
   More than 140 relatives and friends of those lost in the attack
are expected to attend the service.
   ``Our chapel keeps them regularly in our prayers and they are a
regular part of our prayer life,'' said Navy Chaplain Bill Perry,
who will conduct the ceremonies. ``We still hold these families in
our prayers and thoughts.''
   This Navy community was shattered last May 17 when two missiles
fired by an Iraqi warplane slammed into the Stark. Iraq said later
the attack was an accident.
   The reason for gathering on the first anniversary is written
right on the memorial, Perry said. ``You will not be forgotten!'',
it reads.
   ``That's the whole reason for getting together on the 17th,''
Perry said.
   Following a dockside ceremony, family members will board a
sister ship of the Stark for a wreath-laying ceremony in the
Atlantic.
   The USS Stark itself is still undergoing repairs in a
Pascagoula, Miss., shipyard. It is expected to return to Mayport in
August.
   Perry said families of those who survived the attack also have
been invited.
   ``The trauma of that week is theirs,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
