<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1710EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PattyHearst     05-14 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Patty Hearst,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Patricia Hearst Presents Film About Her Kidnapping at Cannes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FIONA GLEIZES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANNES, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patty Hearst was the center of attention
Saturday at the Cannes Film Festival, where a film directed by Paul
Schrader told the story of her 1974 kidnapping by an urban
terrorist group.
   ``I've not completely lost the feeling of anger and I doubt if I
ever will,'' Ms. Hearst said at a news conference. ``But I don't
carry this through my whole life.''
   The film ``Patty Hearst'' recounts how the granddaughter of
newspaper magnate William Randolph Hearst was kidnapped by the
Symbionese Liberation Army in San Francisco.
   She was blindfolded, held prisoner in a cupboard for 57 days and
subjected to revolutionary re-education. Renamed Tania, she took
part in an armed bank robbery and stayed with the SLA for 18 months
before the FBI arrested her in 1975.
   The film covers the five years from the kidnapping to February
1979, when President Carter granted her a pardon from her
seven-year prison sentence.
   Ms. Hearst said she felt no personal responsibility for the
criminal act she committed.
   ``Nothing would have happened if the kidnapping had not taken
place,'' she said.
   Ms. Hearst said she had read the screenplay that was based on
her own account of the affair, ``My Voyage in Hell,'' published in
1978.
   She said she been asked for her comments while the film was
being made, but she stayed away from the production ``because it
may have been uncomfortable for personal reasons.''
   Ms. Hearst was pleased with the film when she saw it.
   ``I was afraid it would be sex, guns and rock 'n roll but it
wasn't,'' she said.
   Schrader, who also has directed ``Hardcore'' and ``American
Gigolo,'' said he saw the events from Ms. Hearst's point of view.
   ``The film portrays the visions and sentiments of Patty,'' he
said. ``It was never intended to be a sociological film or a
comment on the times, but rather the view of a 19-year-old girl who
had led a sheltered life.''
   Her character was played by British actress Natasha Richardson,
the daughter of actress Vanessa Redgrave.
   ``Miss Hearst was never acting of her own volition. She was a
person acted on,'' Schrader said. ``It was difficult dramatically
to have a passive protagonist.''
   Ms. Hearst now lives quietly with husband Bernard Shaw, her
former bodyguard, and their two daughters Lydia, 3, and Gillian, 6.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
