<DOCNO> AP880514-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1726EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CabooseSuit     05-14 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Caboose Suit,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Major Railroads Sue Minnesota Over New Occupied Caboose Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten major railroads are suing Minnesota
to challenge a new state law requiring an occupied caboose on
freight trains of a certain length carrying hazardous materials.
   The suit, filed Friday in federal court, contends that the law,
which goes into effect Aug. 1, is pre-empted by Federal Railroad
Administration regulations that allow freight trains to operate in
interstate commerce without occupied cabooses.
   The railroads also say federal law governing the efficient
interstate transportation of hazardous materials pre-empts the
caboose law.
   They say the new law discriminates against interstate
transportation because it exempts certain local runs carrying such
commodities as grain.
   Among the railroads seeking to have the federal court void the
state law are Burlington Northern, the Soo Line, Chicago & North
Western and the Duluth, Missabe & Iron Range Railway.
   Minnesota's new law states that trains more than 2,000 feet long
that have cars marked as carrying hazardous materials must have a
caboose at the end of the train and it must be occupied by at least
one train crew member.
   Violations of the law would permit the state attorney general's
office or a county sheriff to seek a civil penalty against the
offending railroad.
   The stated purpose of the law, which was pushed by railroad
labor unions, was to promote rail safety by helping to spot
equipment failure or problems with track beds. But opponents said
it was merely an attempt by the railroad unions to preserve jobs no
longer needed.
   ``A caboose is just no longer needed,'' Al Wiegold, spokesman
for Burlington Northern Railroad, said Saturday. He said there are
computerized trackside monitors that indicate problems.
   Money also is a factor in dropping the caboose, Wiegold said.
``It's costly to keep those cabooses on there.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
