<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1743EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-KenoshaWeddings     05-14 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kenosha Weddings,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>13 Couples Get Married In Stadium</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SOLOMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attracted by the slogan, ``We'll provide
the diamond if you provide the bride,'' 13 couples married Saturday
at home plate before a minor league baseball game.
   The couples came from neighboring Illinois to avoid the expense
or bother of an AIDS test, which has been mandatory in their home
state since Jan. 1.
   Players from the Kenosha Twins and the Rockford (Ill.) Expos
lined paths at Simmons Field that led the brides and grooms to a
portable chapel at home plate.
   ``This is to be entered into seriously, honorably, advisably
and, in this case, with good sportsmanship,'' Kenosha County Court
Commissioner Jon Mason said to open the ceremony.
   Some brides wore traditional wedding gowns while others were
dressed in more casual attire. One groom wore a black top hat and
tuxedo, and next to him stood another prospective husband wearing
an open collar shirt and slacks.
   ``We did not want to spend $200 or $300 to get a marriage
license,'' Jane Smith of Park Forest, Ill., said after she married
Floyd Claiborne Jr. of Richton Park, Ill.
   ``We looked at Indiana and Wisconsin before, and then this came
up, and it was just perfect,'' she said.
   Smith's bridesmaid, Gwendlyn Kirkland, said the ceremony was
perfect for non-traditional and ``economic minded couples.''
   Kenosha charges $50 for a wedding license but does not require
any test for acquired immune deficiency syndrome. Illinois charges
$15 for a license, but it also requires a blood test for AIDS and
syphilis, which can cost between $20 and $120 a person, depending
on the laboratory.
   Bob Lee, general manager of the Kenosha Twins, said he thought
of the mass wedding after watching county clerk Nancy Principe
discuss on a news show the sudden rush of Illinois couples applying
for Wisconsin marriage licenses.
   ``If you look at baseball, it's a tradition. And marriage, well
it's a tradition also, so it makes sense to have it here,'' Lee
said. ``I'm sure these wedding couples will remember this for a
long time to come.''
   Andy Harter, an infielder for the Twins, said the ceremony was
enjoyable, ``but I think we're all wondering who would get married
on a baseball diamond. Maybe the real question isn't whether `I
do,' but `Why here?'''
   Team officials said 14 couples registered for the wedding, and
all but one showed up. The missing couple was from Wisconsin.
   The couples ranged in age from early 20s to late 50s.
   Corinne Kozak, 47, and Norman Dennis, 56, both of Arlington
Heights, Ill., said the wedding ceremony was the first time they
had ever been on a baseball field.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
