<1ST_LINE>u p AM-ArizonaRepublicans 1stLd-Writethru   05-14 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arizona Republicans, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0569,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mecham Wins Seat As GOP Delegate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Mecham election as delegate
and speech by Goldwater; picks up 3rd graf pvs, bgng: Mecham,
who...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ousted Arizona Gov. Evan Mecham was
elected Saturday as a GOP national delegate as the state Republican
Party held its first convention since his removal from office.
   Mecham won on his second attempt to win a seat to the party's
national convention, trying first without success to be picked from
his own congressional district and then as a delegate at large. He
was not claimed by any presidential candidate.
   His stormy, 15-month governorship tore the state GOP, and former
Sen. Barry Goldwater, in a keynote address greeted by several
standing ovations, urged Republicans to try to ``heal the wounds.''
   ``If we keep picking away at each other ... the state's going to
become a one-party state again,'' Goldwater added.
   He urged members to settle their differences at election time
and ``let bygones be bygones or at least be patient and wait until
election time to make corrections that you feel may be needed.''
   ``I have done very little work,'' Mecham said when asked to
assess his chances before the balloting. ``If I win, it'll be
because people decide I should go. It's not a big thing.''
   Mecham, who was removed as governor by a Senate court of
impeachment last month, is facing criminal charges in Maricopa
County Superior Court next Thursday.
   The thought of Mecham going to the Republican National
Convention as one of Arizona's 33 delegates drew open disdain from
other politicians in the state.
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., had said he would be ``inclined not
to attend'' the national convention if Mecham were a delegate.
   On Saturday, however, McCain said he was certain he would attend
whether or not Mecham was a delegate.
   ``I am sure we will want to do that. I never changed my mind. I
said that I was thinking long and hard about it _ I never said that
I wasn't going,'' McCain said.
   Vice President George Bush has won enough delegates nationwide
to be clinch the nomination in New Orleans and was expected to
control the state convention as well after receiving majorities in
24 of 37 pre-convention caucuses and tying with former television
evangelist Pat Robertson in one.
   Mecham, one of the 717 delegates to Saturday's convention, said
before the voting started that he believed he had ``strong
support'' from rank-and-file party workers.
   He said Saturday he would support Bush and would concentrate on
who Bush's running mate would be.
   Officials of the Bush and Robertson campaigns said Mecham would
not be on their list of recommended delegates, but Robertson's
campaign said its recommended slate would stop at 32 to enable
Mecham backers to fill in his name as the 33rd delegate if they
wished.
   Mecham, who faces criminal trial next Thursday on charges he
failed to report properly a $350,000 campaign loan, was removed
from office last month after the Republican-controlled Senate
convicted him in a civil proceeding of misusing state money and
obstructing an investigation into allegations that a campaign aide
threatened the life of a former aide.
</TEXT>
