<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1827EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Laos     05-14 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Laos,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Laos Waiting For Aid Before Continuing MIA Search
^By DENIS D. GRAY
^Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENTIANE, Laos (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States should give Laos
humanitarian aid if it wants the country to account for Americans
missing in the Indochina war, a senior government official said
Saturday.
   ``We have fulfilled our obligation with the excavation,'' said
Vice Foreign Minister Soubanh Srithirath. ``We are awaiting the
humanitarian gesture from the U.S.A.''
   Soubanh was referring to a joint excavation in southern
Savannakhet province for the remnants of a U.S. aircraft shot down
in 1966 with two crewmen aboard. U.S. and Laotian soldiers
completed the dig Wednesday but found no remains.
   Soubanh spoke in an interview with a group of Western reporters
taken on a rare tour of Laos, a largely isolated nation ruled by a
communist government since December 1975.
   The United States is trying to account for 555 Americans missing
in action in Laos, many of them airmen downed during missions
against Laotian and Vietnamese communist positions.
   Under an agreement in August last year, Laos ended a long period
of inactivity on the MIA issue while the United States said it will
consider Vientiane's calls for humanitarian aid.
   That was virtually identical to an agreement with Vietnam, Laos'
close ally where nearly 1,800 Americans are reported missing.
Vietnamese officials recently have been demanding that America
honor its pledge of humanitarian assistance.
   The United States has given Laos some food aid in recent years.
After the Savannakhet dig, the U.S. team donated medicine and
equipment worth about $13,000 to a local hospital as an expression
of America's concern, said Ross Petzing, spokesman for the U.S.
Embassy in Bangkok.
   Soubanh suggested the United States give more medical aid,
including construction of a hospital in Savannakhet.
   In another development, Soubanh said Vietnam has withdrawn a
significant number of its troops from Laos, where he says they have
been helping with national security and economic development for
more than a decade.
   Soubanh declined to give numbers but said the pullout began in
mid-1987. The troops returned home because Laos' relations with
China have improved and the Laotian government's own military
forces were adequate, he said.
   ``We feel that our security is less threatened,'' he said.
   Some Western diplomatic sources in Vientiane speculate that less
than half the estimated 50,000 Vietnamese troops have left. Others
say they believe more than 40,000 have pulled out.
   Vietnam formally stations troops in Laos under a 25-year
friendship treaty signed in 1977. But most Western sources believe
some of the Vietnamese forces that helped the Laotian communists
battle the U.S.-backed regime in Vientiane remained in Laos after
the communists took power in 1975.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880514-0142 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1850EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-14 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sunshine, Warm Temperatures Cover Much of Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sunny skies heated much of the Mississippi Valley into the 90s
Saturday while scattered showers hit parts of the southern Atlantic
Coast, the southern Appalachians and the central Plains.
   A low pressure system centered over south central Canada drew
warm air well up the Mississippi Valley, bringing record-setting
90-degree weather as far north as Iowa.
   Des Moines, Iowa, set a record high for the date of 93. Other
records included 89 degrees at Kansas City, Mo., 91 at Memphis,
Tenn., and 92 at Baton Rouge, La.
   Thunderstorms rumbled over coastal areas of Georgia and the
Carolinas and the southern Appalachians from eastern Tennessee and
western North Carolina to West Virginia, bringing scattered rain.
   A few thunderstorms also hit eastern Wisconsin and south central
Minnesota and there were scattered showers from the Texas Panhandle
into the central Plains.
   There were no reports of significant rainfall, defined as
one-half inch or more, in the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT.
   Sunny skies prevailed in most other parts with temperatures in
the 70s and 80s over Florida and much of the California coast, and
in the upper 50s and 60s in the Pacific Northwest, the Great Lakes,
Pennsylvania, New York and New England.
   Temperatures ranged from the 90s to 105 in the Southwest's
deserts, down from peaks of around 110 in the past few days.
   Scattered showers were forecast Sunday for the coast of the
Carolinas, the Great Lakes and the eastern portion of the upper
Mississippi Valley. Cloudy skies were predicted for the Oregon
coast and sunny skies were expected to prevail over much of the
rest of the nation.
   Highs were forecast to be in the 60s over upper Michigan, much
of Minnesota and North Dakota, and from the Idaho Panhandle to the
northern Washington coast. Highs were predicted to be near 90 in
eastern Texas, in the 90s in western Texas, and from the 90s to
near 110 degrees in the desert Southwest.
   Highs were forecast to be in the 70s and 80s over most of the
rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
