<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1931EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson     05-14 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Calls for Ocean Sanctuary to Stop Oil Drilling off
California</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MENDOCINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson pledged Saturday that if
elected president he would ``end for all times'' plans for
exploratory offshore oil drilling along California's picturesque
North Coast.
   ``This plan to drill for oil, pollute the ocean, and dirty the
air is environmental violence, it's economic violence,'' Jackson
said, using a solar-powered sound system to address the crowd.
   Despite polls showing him far behind Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis, Jackson drew large and enthusiastic crowds as he crossed
California campaigning for the last and biggest Democratic
presidential primary on June 7. There are 336 delegates at stake.
   Acknowledging the long odds against his campaign, in which he
trails Dukakis by 655 delegates with just 512 still to be elected,
Jackson told the cheering crowd: ``Why do I run against these odds?
I've faced odds all my life ... we cannot surrender, we the people
can win, we really can win.''
   Jackson attacked the Reagan administration and Vice President
George Bush on a wide range of issues, but his focus Saturday was
on environmental and educational concerns.
   He received his most enthusiastic response to a pledge to
support a congressional proposal to create a permanent ocean
sanctuary that effectively would forever bar oil drilling off the
California coast. In particular Jackson promised his opposition to
Lease Sale 91, a proposal by the Interior Department providing for
oil drilling.
   Standing beneath a clear sky on a bluff overlooking the Pacific
Ocean at one of the most scenic spots on the California coast 150
miles north of San Francisco, Jackson said the oil drilling plans
for that region amount to a ``drain America policy at any
environmental price.
   ``A Jackson administration will end for all times Lease Sale 91.
There will be no drilling for oil on the North Coast (of
California) under a Jackson presidency,'' he told a rally of more
than 1,500 at the remote, sparsely populated resort area.
   Later, Jackson repeated familiar themes supporting education and
providing equal opportunities for minorities at a rally of several
thousand supporters at Stanford University.
   ``You will make the world better. You will make the world
better. You are the hope,'' he told the crowd.
   Before about 5,000 supporters at Stanford, Jackson repeated his
proposal to freeze defense spending at current levels and use that
money for housing, health care, student aid and other social needs.
   ``Our future is in co-existence, not co-annihilation. Enough of
this false security'' from building more weapons, he said. ``Let's
go another way, let's invest in people, let's use some of that
money to keep America strong and make America better.''
</TEXT>
