<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 1943EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Taiwan-Defector     05-14 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taiwan-Defector,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Pilot Defector Seeks Bigger Gold Reward</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Chinese air force pilot who
defected to Taiwan in a jet bomber in 1965 said Saturday the
government should have given him a bigger gold reward.
   In a petition to the Legislative Yuan, Taiwan's highest
lawmaking body, Col. Lee Hsien-pin said he was living in hardship
and asked the government to give him the shares of the gold rewards
that were given to two technicians who flew to Taiwan with Lee.
   Technicians Lee Tsai-wang and Lien Pao-sheng did not deserve any
share of the reward of 330 pounds of gold, Col. Lee said, claiming
the two technicians were merely his captives.
   The reward was paid in cash and Col. Lee received about $70,000,
or 50 percent of the reward, while Lee Tsai-wang and Lien split the
other half.
   The government said the reward for Lien, who died of severe
injuries when the Ilyushin-28 bomber crash-landed at Taoyuan air
base in northern Taiwan, would be handed to Lien's relatives in
China when the Nationalists regain the Chinese mainland.
   Lee Tsai-wang went to the United States after he retired from
Taiwan's air force in 1975.
   Vice Defense Minister Chou Hsueh-tsun on Saturday told lawmakers
the rewards also went to Lee Tsai-wang and Lien because they helped
Lee Hsien-pin in flying to Taiwan.
   Chou also argued the government has taken good care of Lee, who
Chou says owns three houses and earns a monthly salary of $1,700.
   Taiwan has a sliding scale of rewards paid in gold for defecting
Chinese servicemen that depends on the type of military aircraft or
ships brought out of China. A jet bomber is worth 330 pounds of
gold.
   Officials say 13 military personnel have defected from China to
Taiwan since 1949, when the Nationalists fled to this island after
losing a civil war to the Communists on the Chinese mainland.
</TEXT>
