<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-RedArmy     05-14 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Red Army,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Red Army Demands Release Of Shibata, Threatens Reprisal In Telex</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the Japanese terrorist group Red Army
demanded that authorities release a co-member arrested recently or
face a ``fitting reprisal,'' a newspaper reported in its Sunday
editions.
   In a telex dispatched Saturday from North Korea to the
newspaper, the Yomiuri Shimbun, the group said Yasuhiro Shibata, an
alleged Red Army faction member, went to Japan ``to pioneer the way
for us to return.''
   Unless the Japanese government and police took immediate action
to release Shibata, the Red Army was prepared to retaliate, faction
members said in a message titled, ``An Urgent Statement on the
Unfair Arrest of Comrade Yasuhiro Shibata.''
   In the telex sent to the newspaper's Tokyo headquarters, the
group also claimed Japanese authorities were ``repressing'' groups
in Japan sympathetic to the Red Army cause and demanded that such
action be stopped on threat of reprisal, Yomiuri reported in both
its Japanese and English-language editions.
   On May 6 police arrested Shibata, 34, near his apartment. He is
one of nine alleged Red Army terrorists suspected of taking part in
the 1970 hijacking of a Japan Air Lines passenger jet to North
Korea.
   At the time of his arrest, Shibata was carrying a passport
issued in the name of Akira Nakao, a Japanese who had assumed North
Korean citizenship and was residing in his adopted country.
   Yomiuri also reported that in a follow-up telephone conversation
with Red Army member Morisuke Wakabayashi in Pyongyang, North
Korea, the suspected terrorist replied in the positive when asked
if seven faction members were based in that country.
   Yomiuri said it contacted Wakabayashi, one of the leaders of the
1970 hijacking group, as he was dispatching the telex to Tokyo from
the Pyongyang International Post Office.
   Wakabayashi denied any role by North Korean officials in
planning the message.
   ``We conferred among ourselves and wrote a 4,000-character
message at first. Then we cut it in half to 2,000,'' the newspaper
quoted him as saying.
   The group's message said Shibata returned to Japan because he
was homesick and discounted as slanderous Japanese reports that the
faction member was planning a terrorist attack or was spying for
North Korea.
</TEXT>
