<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 2109EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0655 05-14 0748</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0655,740</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 5 grafs after 14th graf, bgng: The vice xxx to UPDATE
with Jackson and Cuomo speeches; SUBS 3 grafs for last graf pvs to
UPDATE with convention results; no pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis was heckled Saturday by gay political
activists over his stand on their rights to be foster parents,
while Republican George Bush fended off a corporate executive's
criticism of Reagan administration policies on taxes and trade.
   Both parties' presidential front-runners were spending the
weekend campaigning in the West, where the the bulk of the final
round of primaries will be held in the next two weeks.
   Dukakis, speaking to several dozen homosexual activists at a
political action committee meeting in Los Angeles, promised,
``You're going to be deeply involved in what we do.''
   But the Massachusetts governor was challenged over a policy in
his state giving low priority to homosexual couples who want to be
foster parents.
   Dukakis said he favored the Massachusetts policy ``because I
think it's best, all things being equal, for a child to grow up in
a household with a mother and father and other children.''
   His defense of that policy was met with some hisses from the
crowd and occasional shouts of protest. One man shouted, ``bigot,''
and another yelled, ``You're anti-gay. Why don't you admit it?''
   Dukakis later shrugged off the hostile reception, saying, ``It
was lively. That's what democracy is all about.''
   His aides, nevertheless, were pleased with the way the meeting
went. ``I thought it was very good, very open,'' said Alice Travis,
national political coordinator for the campaign.
   Meanwhile, Bush toured an Intel microchip plant in Oregon, where
the company's board chairman, Robert Noyce, told the vice president
of a need for higher taxes and for President Reagan to sign the
trade bill.
   ``I don't think that there is any chance of a balanced budget
without new taxes,'' said Noyce.
   Reagan on Saturday repeated his vow to veto a trade bill passed
by Congress because of a provision requiring large companies to
notify employees in advance of plant closings.
   ``The plant-closing aspect of the trade bill does not seem
onerous to us,'' Noyce said. ``It is no less than we would do in
any case.''
   Bush said he was not swayed by Noyce's arguments.
   The vice president also sought to take the high ground on the
issue of the environment, saying, ``For too long we have given away
the playing field to the Democrats on the environment. I want to
make the environment a Republican issue.''
   Jesse Jackson, campaigning in California, took the environment
as his theme, saying he would seek a ban of exploratory offshore
oil drilling along the state's north coast forever.
   Jackson addressed an enthusiastic crowd in Mendocino using a
solar-powered loudspeaker.
   ``This plan to drill for oil, pollute the ocean, and dirty the
air is environmental violence, it's economic violence,'' Jackson
said.
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, speaking in Portland, Ore., on
Saturday, said he believes Dukakis will win the Democratic
presidential nomination but will need Jackson's help to win in
November.
   ``A Jesse Jackson who is an impassioned part of the effort to
support Mike Dukakis if Mike wins, and that's the way it looks,
that would be helpful, absolutely,'' Cuomo said.
   The next two weeks mark the close to the primary season with
Oregon's primary on Tuesday, followed a week later with primaries
in California, New Jersey, New Mexico and Montana.
   Meanwhile, other states were wrapping up the final rounds of
their delegate selection with state and district conventions over
the weekend.
   In Arizona, ousted Gov. Evan Mecham, who was removed from office
by a state Senate impeachment trial and faces still another trial
on criminal charges, was selected as an at-large delegate to the
Republican National Convention. No presidential candidate was
claiming him, and other state politicians were openly hostile
toward his candidacy.
   Mecham, who earlier lost in his bid to be one of the three
delegates from a congressional district, said he would support Bush
and would concentrate on the Republican's choice for vice president.
   Delaware Republicans picked 17 national convention delegates on
Saturday, including former Gov. Pete du Pont, who withdrew from the
race for the GOP presidential nomination.
   Dukakis and Jackson each made slight gains in Maine and
Michigan, where Democrats wrapped up their delegate selections on
Saturday.
   Conventions also were being held this weekend by Democrats in
Iowa and Alaska.
</TEXT>
