<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PortraitProtest     05-14 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Portrait Protest,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Art Institute Apologizes For Furor Over Portrait Of Lingerie-Clad
Mayor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An art school apologized in newspaper
advertisements Sunday for exhibiting a student's portrait of late
Mayor Harold Washington in lingerie, but criticized the way it was
removed by black aldermen.
   ``All educational institutions encourage students' freedom of
expression,'' the School of the Art Institute said in full-page ads
in the Chicago Sun-Times and Chicago Tribune.
   ``Regrettably, in the use of his freedom, this student created a
work that had the effect of insulting the memory of an important
leader, Mayor Harold Washington.''
   The student, David Nelson, depicted Washington in a frilly white
bra, panties, garter and stockings, holding a pencil and frowning.
Washington died of a heart attack last November.
   The painting was hung in a students' exhibition at the school
but was confiscated by police Wednesday when black aldermen stormed
in and said it disgraced the city's first black mayor and
threatened public order.
   ``We do not approve of the method used by members of the City
Council who entered a private space within the School and forcibly
removed the painting from the wall, even though we recognize the
intensity of feeling on the part of those aldermen in this
situation,'' the ad said.
   The ad was addressed ``To The Chicago Community'' and carried
the names of Marshall Field, president of The Art Institute of
Chicago's board of trustees, and Tony Jones, president of the
School of the Art Institute.
   Nelson has not given interviews since the dispute began and did
not attend his class' graduation ceremonies at the school Saturday.
Eileen Harakal, a spokeswoman for the art institute, said his
diploma would be mailed to him.
   The painting has been returned to him, but the American Civil
Liberties Union has said it would file a civil rights lawsuit
challenging the police department's authority to remove the piece.
   The portrait has been a rallying point for blacks all week.
Washington supporters scheduled _ and then canceled _ a march
Saturday from City Hall to the art school.
   ``We thought it best to let things cool off for awhile,'' said
Chuck Kelly, a former aide to the late mayor. ``We are going to
continue to monitor the situation ... but I think the Art Institute
has seen the error of its ways.''
   Reporters who arrived at a plaza opposite City Hall to cover the
scheduled march instead found art students who also canceled a
planned rally of their own.
   Joe Medosch, a student at the school, said students wanted to
``avoid a confrontation'' with blacks.
   ``We didn't want to see anyone hurt,'' Medosch said. ``We're not
backing David (Nelson), we're backing our rights.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
