<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0615,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Disagrees With Executive's Call for Trade Bill, Higher Taxes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 14th graf, bgng: ``It's not xxx to
UPDATE with Bush criticism of prison furloughs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALOHA, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican nominee-to-be George Bush, intent
on discussing high technology Saturday at the Intel microchip
plant, instead heard about the need for higher taxes and President
Reagan's signature on the trade bill.
   Bush was quick to disagree with Intel board chairman Robert
Noyce, who said the semiconductor industry needs the trade bill and
higher taxes can help balance the budget. Noyce had shown the vice
president the company's semiconductor manufacturing facility
outside of Portland.
   High technology and the environment were the topics for the
third day of Bush's Western swing in advance of the Oregon primary
on Tuesday and the California primary three weeks hence.
   The Republican heir-apparent donned a ``full FAB bunny suit,''
in which he was garbed from head to toe in special overalls that
keep dust at a minimum, as he viewed the sophisticated Intel
facility.
   Later, when Noyce briefed the vice president on the company's
situation, taxes and a provision of the trade bill _ the 60-day
notification of a plant closing _ came up.
   ``I don't think that there is any chance of a balanced budget
without new taxes,'' Noyce told Bush, saying he is worried about
the supply of capital for investment in America. ``That's not a
popular subject this year ... We need to promote savings.''
   Bush said his mind has not been changed.
   ``It didn't at all. I don't think the next president has to,
provided we get a grip on spending ... I disagree with him on
that,'' he told reporters after a speech to Intel employees.
   Noyce also said the semiconductor industry needs the proposed
trade bill, brushing aside Reagan's criticism of the measure. The
president, in his weekly radio address, repeated his vow to veto
the bill, citing the plant-closing provision.
   ``The plant-closing aspect of the trade bill does not seem
onerous to us,'' Noyce said. ``It is no less than we would do in
any case.''
   Bush again disagreed, backing Reagan on the issue.
   ``I was very interested in his position. It doesn't change my
mind,'' he said.
   But the vice president praised the Massachusetts plant-closing
law, which his likely Democratic opponent Michael Dukakis uses as
an example to support the call for a federal law.
   ``It's not a big problem for companies like this, but what you
don't want to see is disincentives to start new businesses,'' Bush
told reporters. ``In Massachusetts, they have a plant-closing law.
It's voluntary. It's not like the federal government imposing it.''
   At his last event of the day, Bush criticized the furlough
program in Massachusetts _ backed by Dukakis _ that allowed some
criminals weekend breaks from jail.
   ``Believe you will never see from me a program like the one in
Massachusetts to let these murderers out of jail ahead their
sentence running out so they can go out and kill again _ like one
of them did in that state,'' Bush told a crowd at a rally in
Medford.
   The state legislature recently eliminated that furlough program.
   On the subject of the environment, Bush said the Republican
Party needs to take the issue back after years of allowing the
Democrats the right to lay claim to it.
   ``For too long, we have given away the playing field to the
Democrats on the environment. I want to make the environment a
Republican issue,'' he told the cheering crowd of about 800
Republicans late Friday night in Portland.
   ``I would like to be remembered the same way as Teddy Roosevelt
_ next to the national security, it's the condition of the Earth
that you will leave to generations to come. We can do better,'' he
said.
   Bush was scheduled to visit a tree nursery near Medford, Ore.,
on Saturday, take a raft trip Sunday and visit a tree research lab
in Washington on Monday.
</TEXT>
