<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 2131EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDS-Education     05-14 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Education,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CDC Official Warns Educators Of Need For Prevention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The AIDS virus will reach epidemic proportions
among young people, educators were told Saturday, unless a
comprehensive prevention program on the disease is implemented in
every school, at every grade level.
   Health officials at the national Centers for Disease Control
believe adolescents experimenting with sex and drugs seriously risk
contracting the acquired immune deficiency syndrome virus, said
Dennis Tolsman, the CDC's director of health promotion and
education.
   ``We can't think (AIDS prevention) can be carried out through a
pamphlet or a 15-minute lecture,'' Tolsman told an audience of more
than 100 educators attending a conference on AIDS and education.
   ``We need a comprehensive program taught in health education
classes by trained health education personnel to fight this
problem,'' he said. ``We need your help to make sure adolescents
understand what AIDS is and how it is prevented.''
   CDC officials teamed with the National Education Association to
sponsor the three-day conference, which concludes Sunday.
   Educators received guidelines for educating students about AIDS
and discussed AIDS infection among teenagers.
   The guidelines propose efforts at all grade levels, including
early elementary school programs that reduce fears of an epidemic
and teach students that the disease is not spread through casual
contact.
   Late elementary and middle school programs should inform
students about the disease itself, and junior and senior high
school students should be told of the risks of contracting AIDS
through sex or intravenous drug use, say the guidelines.
   Some educators expressed reservations about the plan.
   ``School health officials cannot do this alone,'' said Jennifer
Jo Hugstad-Vaa, a biology teacher from Burnsville, Minn. ``AIDS is
an epidemic and it covers every thing from biology, home economics
(and) social studies to economics.
   ``It's not just a health problem,'' she said.
   James Williams, director of the NEA Health Information Network,
added that the entire school staff should receive AIDS training
because children often receive advice from their bus drivers,
janitors and cafeteria workers.
   In the United States, AIDS has affected 973 children under age
13, 260 teenagers and more than 61,000 adults, according to the
CDC. The disease has killed more than 34,000 people.
   ``The numbers in these groups (children and teenagers) are tiny
when compared to adults, but still the numbers are staggering,''
said Dr. Peter Droutman, medical epidemiologist for the CDC.
</TEXT>
