<1ST_LINE>u p AM-IowaDemocrats 1stLd-Writethru   05-14 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iowa Democrats, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0568,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iowa Democrats Falling in Line at District Conventions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 6th graf, bgng: About 3,000 xxx to
UPDATE with district convention results.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis didn't win Iowa's
first-in-the-nation caucuses last February, didn't even come in
second. But now that he's the likely nominee, slightly embarrassed
Iowa Democrats are falling in line behind the Massachusetts
governor.
   Not the least on their minds is 1992, and the prospect of losing
the status of putting the first mark on the primary season.
   ``That's a key factor,'' said Iowa party chairwoman Bonnie
Campbell, who admits her endorsement of Dukakis last week was
partly designed to curry favor with him in hopes he'll look kindly
on Iowa in 1992. ``Naturally, I give great thought to that.''
   Dukakis came in third in the Feb. 8 caucuses, behind winner
Richard Gephardt and runner-up Paul Simon. But Missouri Rep.
Gephardt dropped out of the presidential race March 28 and Simon,
the senator from Illinois, suspended his campaign on April 7,
leaving Dukakis and Jesse Jackson to battle for the nomination.
   About 3,000 Democratic activists were trooping to congressional
district conventions Saturday to begin picking a slate of delegates
that will bear only a passing resemblance to the much-ballyhooed
outcome of the precinct caucuses.
   At those meetinngs, Dukakis claimed 12 of the delegates elected,
while Gephardt forces won nine technically uncommitted delegates,
most of whom are expected to endorse Dukakis during the next month.
   Jackson claimed seven delegates, while Simon was awarded six.
   Gephardt's backers had hoped to maintain their status as a group
in hopes of electing their leaders to delegate slots, but most are
epxected to turn to Dukakis.
   That isn't surprising, party leaders say, because a certain
amount of flexibility has always been a trademark of Iowa Democrats.
   ``We have to realign probably more than any other group of
Democrats,'' said Campbell. ``It requires us to be quite facile and
most Iowa Democrats are, in fact, pretty flexible.''
   ``Our delegation's makeup follows the idiosyncrasies of what's
happening on the campaign trail and matches what's happening,''
said Democratic Party spokesman Phil Roeder. ``Part of the good
thing about the four-step system we have is there are points along
the road where people can step back, change their allegiances and,
in a way, go with the flow.''
   Iowa was the launching pad for the Democratic presidential race
three months ago, but the rest of the nation wasn't buying the
direction the state wanted to head.
   Ms. Campbell said Iowa Democrats don't have to be told twice
that it's time to switch gears, and they were moving to do that
Saturday. She traveled to conventions in all six of the state's
congressional districts urging activists to elect national
convention delegates loyal to Dukakis.
   ``I think it sends a pretty strong message that it's a good time
to start thinking about November,'' said Jerry Crawford, a Des
Moines lawyer and Dukakis backer.
   Party rules call for Iowans to pick 34 of the state's 61
delegates to the Democratic National Convention at those district
conventions.
   The only suspense was whether Gephardt's loyalists could hang
together long enough to elect their leaders to cherished delegate
slots, technically uncommitted but Dukakis backers in reality.
   ``Most of them are Gephardt people, but I think you'll see a lot
of them commit to Dukakis even before the state convention,''
Roeder said.
   Iowa's delegate selection process is a complex affair, and only
the first stage is shoved into the nation's political limelight.
The precinct caucuses were essentially a straw poll of whom was
favored among the 100,000 or so activists who showed up and elected
delegates to the next step, conventions in all 99 counties.
   Delegates aren't actually elected until the district
conventions, and the race routinely has changed by that point. The
final 18 delegates are chosen at the party's June 25 state
convention.
   Ms. Campbell spoke as if she expected the shift all along.
   ``Dukakis did remarkably well here,'' she said. ``Those folks
were very close together in reality. Those three people did very
well.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
