<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Teamsters-Presser     05-14 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teamsters-Presser,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teamsters President Hospitalized, Reportedly Has Brain Cancer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teamsters union President Jackie Presser,
who temporarily relinquished his duties for health reasons on May
4, has been admitted to a Phoenix hospital, officials said Saturday.
   Kathy Pitts, a supervisor at Barrows Neurological Center at St.
Joseph's Hospital and Medical Center here, said no word on
Presser's illness or condition would be released.
   However, the Akron (Ohio) Beacon Journal reported Saturday that
Presser was diagnosed last week as having brain cancer and was
transferred to Barrows from the Cleveland Clinic.
   Presser, 61, previously has undergone surgery for a malignant
tumor in his lung.
   Meanwhile, the Teamsters union executive board is set to meet
Monday in Phoenix amid reports of a power struggle stemming from
the health problems of Presser, who has been Teamsters president
since 1983.
   Weldon L. Mathis, the 1.6-million-member union's secretary
treasurer who has taken over Presser's duties, called Monday's
meeting, but some board members are considering a boycott, the
Beacon-Journal and The (Cleveland) Plain Dealer reported.
   The board is made up of 16 vice presidents and Mathis.
   Don West, an international vice president from Birmingham, Ala.,
confirmed the meeting but would not comment on it, The Plain Dealer
said.
   The newspaper quoted a union source as saying the meeting was
called because of Presser's letter to Mathis announcing his
decision to step aside for four months. Other sources were quoted
as citing concern about who would take over should Presser resign
or die.
   ``Some people feel (Teamster lawyer John R.) Climaco encouraged
Jackie to sign it (the letter) to give Weldon a leg up,'' The Plain
Dealer quoted the source as saying.
   Climaco on Friday denied manuevering to set up Mathis as the
next Teamsters president, the newspaper reported.
   ``Anyone who takes the time to read the international
constitution knows that it provides that the general
secretary-treasurer assumes the duties anytime the general
president is unavailable,'' he said.
   Presser is scheduled to stand trial July 12 in U.S. District
Court in Cleveland on embezzlement and racketeering charges.
   In court papers, Presser's attorneys have said their client does
not want to postpone the trial, but he was too ill to attend a
hearing called this week by U.S. District Judge George White to
discuss Presser's health.
   The hearing was rescheduled for June 3.
   Presser is accused, along with two other Teamsters officials, of
siphoning $700,000 in union funds from Teamsters Local 507 in
Cleveland. Presser remains secretary-treasurer of Local 507.
   Presser has pleaded innocent to the charges. His attorneys say
Presser was a government informant and that the fraud scheme was
authorized by the FBI.
</TEXT>
