<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Brites SUB a0586 05-14 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites, SUB, a0586,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st item to add that stripper kept on a bikini.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>YEADON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Hunsberger hopes nobody is embarrassed
by his wife's little anniversary prank, because even she was
surprised when the fake cop she hired to ticket him began taking
off her uniform at a church league softball game.
   ``See, it was all in fun,'' Hunsberger said. ``But she (wife
Debbie) thought it was only a thing of where I would get a
citation. She didn't find out about the Strip-O-Gram _ or whatever
_ part of it until it was too late.''
   As it happened, the shortstop for the other team, Manoa
Presbyterian, doubles as that church's pastor, and he didn't find
it entirely humorous.
   ``The pastor saw it, and came over to our coach to express his
concern about it all,'' Hunsberger said. ``I mean, after all, it is
a church league.
   ``See, it was all supposed to happen after the game _ when the
other people had left. But people were still around, and there were
even some kids there ... it all happened so fast.''
   Hunsberger said nothing offensive was intended and he hopes
nobody gets in trouble with league or sponsoring church officials
over it.
   Some had an inkling before it happened. Hunsberger's brother,
Billy, gave John an emphatic ``Stop'' sign from the third-base
coaching box as John rounded third after hitting a grand slam.
   But poor John didn't get it, until the ``policewoman'' arrived,
nattily attired in a blue uniform and badges, searching for ``the
owner of that red Cavalier over there.''
   ``He thought it was real at first,'' said Hunsberger's teammate
Paul Azarian. ``But after about 30 seconds he figured it out.''
   Azarian said the woman stripped down to a bikini.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
