<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pope 4thLd-Writethru a0677 05-14 0789</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0677,0809</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Arrives In Peru; Insurgents Blamed For Bombings, Blackouts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 4th graf ``Later Saturday...'' to
UPDATE with ceremony outside cathedral, bomb explosions in capital,
pope retiring for night. Pickup 5th graf pvs ``Earlier in...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Pope-Latin America</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LIMX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II arrived Saturday evening in
poor, terrorism-plagued Peru and heard a plea from President Alan
Garcia to reach out to ``those who are sick with hate and who kill
and destroy with violence.''
   John Paul, on a 12-day, four-nation mission to South America,
arrived from neighboring Bolivia on an antiquated Aeroperu DC-8 jet.
   At Lima's airport he expressed his sympathy with ``the huge
multitude that has experienced grief, violence, abandonment and
hunger'' in Peru.
   Later Saturday evening, scattered blackouts attributed to
leftist sabotage hit Lima while the pope was addressing priests,
nuns and seminary students but did not affect the downtown area
surrounding the colonial-era cathedral where he was.
   Outside the cathedral in Lima's central plaza the pope
consecrated a Peruvian version of the Virgin Mary. Tens of
thousands of people cheered, waved white handkerchiefs and shouted,
``Viva,'' Spanish for ``long life.'' Then the pontiff retired for
the night in the Vatican Embassy.
   Small dynamite charges exploded in at least four spots in the
city during Saturday night's papal activities, but police said no
one was hurt. Authorities attributed the blasts to insurgents.
   Earlier in the day about 20 women disrupted a Mass in a Roman
Catholic church in Lima, the capital, and appealed in the pope's
name for respect for the rights of leftist rebels held in local
prisons. Guerrillas in a mountain town ambushed an army convoy and
killed three soldiers.
   A military intelligence officer, who spoke to The Associated
Press on condition of anonymity, said two men posing as police with
automatic rifles were arrested on the papal motorcade route from
the Lima airport to downtown. He said there was an order to shoot
and kill any armed suspect near the pope.
   Echoing a theme he stressed before in Bolivia and Uruguay, the
pope cited Peru's ``hunger for bread'' and called on its citizens
to build ``a more fraternal and just society.''
   Garcia, a nationalistic social reformer who has halted virtually
all payment of Peru's $14.6 billion foreign debt, demanded a fairer
shake for poor nations of the Third World.
   ``We reject the usurious terms of the foreign debt,'' the
president told John Paul at the airport.
   John Paul, left the tropical Bolivian city of Santa Cruz for
Peru earlier Saturday.
   ``Don't go away, holy father. Don't leave us,'' Bolivian vice
president Julio Garrett Ayllon told the pope during a farewell
ceremony, repeating a chant heard throughout the pontiff's five-day
Bolivian stay.
   Addressing a Mass on Saturday in the Amazon basin city of
Trinidad, the pope insisted that ``constant, intense, honest and
efficient work by everyone'' was needed to overcome poverty. ``We
can't expect everything from outside.''
   It has been three years since the pope has been to Peru, a
country bloodied by an unrelenting leftist insurgency. When he was
here in 1985 he pleaded with rebels to abandon their armed struggle
to overthrow Peru's elected government.
   But the violence is worse than ever and the country is submerged
in a serious economic crisis.
   Inflation expected to top a record 400 percent this year year
and the country has virtually no dollars left in reserves to
maintain imports and economic growth.
   On Sunday the pope planned to celebrate an open air Mass, meet
with church officials and business and cultural leaders and close a
conference of Latin American bishops. Monday he continues on to
Paraguay, his last stop.
   Police said the women who occupied the church Saturday
surrounded a priest saying Mass and held a large banner reading:
``John Paul II, intercede for our brothers, political prisoners.''
   Witnesses said police took the protesters away in vans. Police
confirmed the incident but said they had no information on arrests.
   The women identified themselves as relatives of prisoners
accused of belonging to the pro-Cuba Tupac Amaru Revolutionary
Movement, a small rebel band active since 1984.
   The government President Garcia, who took office in 1985, is
also plagued by the fanatical Mao-inspired Shining Path, which
launched its insurgency in May 1980.
   Shining Path guerrillas Saturday ambushed an army convoy near
the Ayacucho town of Huancasancos, killing three soldiers wounding
three others, the military said in a communique.
   More than 10,000 people have died in the violence since 1980,
including rebels, policemen, soldiers, public officials and
civilians. More than half of Peru's population of 21 million people
live under states of emergencies in different parts of the country.
</TEXT>
