<DOCNO> AP880514-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-88 2307EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Noriega-US 1stLd-Writethru a0579 05-14 1011</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Noriega-US, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0579,1038</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Defiant Noriega Hardens Position</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf ``On Wednesday...'' with 4 grafs to UPDATE with
report that talks still alive and details of latest U.S. offer.
Pickup 6th graf pvs ``His lawyers...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite months of U.S. sanctions and
a crumbling economy, Gen. Manuel Noriega is hardening his position
and preparing for months or possibly years more of confrontation
with the United States.
   A confident Noriega on Friday sallied into the provinces, where
he was cheered by peasants and hailed by small-town officials.
Accompanied by several colonels in a show of military unity,
Panama's defiant leader, accused in the United States of drug
trafficking, dismissed prospects for a negotiated settlement with
the United States.
   Noriega's comments to journalists indicated he considers himself
and Panama a test case of historical proportions and that he is
determined to rise to the occasion and challenge U.S. might.
   ``Everything fell apart,'' he said in La Negrita, 90 miles west
of the capital, when asked about recent U.S-Panamanian talks aimed
at resolving Panama's political crisis over Noriega's leadership.
   The Washington Post, citing unidentified sources, reported in
its Sunday editions that negotiations were at a delicate stage and
that administration officials believed a deal would be struck
within a few days or the talks would collapse.
   The administration is offering to drop drug-trafficking charges
against Noriega if he relinquished office Aug. 12 and left the
country, the newspaper said. In addition, the administration would
continue to recognize ousted President Eric Arturo Delvalle but
also would allow Solis Palma, Noriega's handpicked chief of state,
to continue as Panama's acting president through the May 1989
elections, the newspaper said.
   The Post said there were conflicting reports on when Noriega
could return to Panama under the deal, but one source said it would
be after the elections.
   On Wednesday, U.S. media also reported that a Washington-Noriega
deal was nearly complete. They said it involved Noriega stepping
down and accepting temporary exile in exchange for dismissal of the
drug charges.
   His lawyers plan to appear in court to request dismissal of the
drug charges in about a month. They contend the charges are
politically motivated.
   ``The general isn't going anywhere,'' his spokesman, Maj.
Edgardo Lopez, told The Associated Press in Rio Hato, where
small-town mayors met with Noriega. A document signed by 505 mayors
called Noriega ``the incarnation of Panama's struggle against
imperialism'' and praised him ``for walking among the humble and
speaking their language.''
   Noriega, a mestizo of lower middle-class origins, has tried to
present the crisis as a conflict pitting a domineering Washington
allied with local rich white ``sellouts'' against Panama's
darker-skinned and poorer majority.
   The military commander, whose fortune is estimated at up to $1
billion, and his propaganda machine have succeeded to some degree
in selling that version locally and in Latin America.
   A divided opposition has been hamstrung by carefully applied
repression that gets the job done without deaths. All opposition
media have been closed.
   ``Panama's dignity is not negotiable while there are foreign
troops on our territory, humiliating our soil, while there is
economic aggression, as long as there are threats, as long as there
is psychological war,'' Noriega told reporters in Rio Hato, adding,
``and as long as (U.S.) Ambassador Arthur Davis doesn't get out.''
   About 10,000 American soldiers are stationed in Panama as part
of the U.S. Southern Command.
   The month of August, when Noriega completes 25 years of military
service, has been mentioned as a possible retirement date. But he
said Friday the date of his retirement is none of Washington's
business.
   Lopez said nothing prevents the general from commanding the
Defense Forces for several more years if he and the high command
see fit.
   Michael Kozak, the U.S. State Department envoy who has been
talking with Noriega's representatives in recent weeks, was still
in Panama on Saturday.
   Lopez, who described the talks as stalled, said Kozak might go
home this weekend. But he also said it was in the Reagan
administration's interest to make it appear that negotiations were
continuing, even if they offered scant hope of progress.
   ``In the middle of an election campaign, President Reagan, who
is backing (vice president) George Bush 100 percent, has to save
face because of the big bungle they've made,'' he said.
   Lopez's assessment of prospects for the talks was bleak.
   ``Kozak comes each time with the same plan _ the original plan a
little more elastic. It is a deadline for (Noriega) resigning his
post, a deadline for leaving the country.'' he said. ``It is a plan
that the general and the Panamanian republic cannot accept.''
   Noriega told reporters: ``The experiment of (U.S.) aggression
that exists in Panama is a testing ground that later could be
applied to Honduras, Guatemala, Costa Rica or any country.''
   The general faces other pressures, however, beyond those from
Washington. The country's economy is collapsing under the strain of
the crisis.
   A team of five respected economists published a study this week
saying production was half of normal because of U.S. sanctions and
banking restrictions. They said more than a quarter of the work
force will be unemployed within months, even if the political
crisis were resolved tomorrow.
   They raised the specter of hunger and said it would take at
least two years of intensive recovery measures and massive
international aid to get the economy back to a semblance of what it
was a year ago.
   They said recovery cannot even begin until the political crisis
stemming from Noriega's hold on power is settled.
   But that appears further off with each passing day.
   Ricardo Arias Calderon, president of the Christian Democratic
Party, is one of the few opposition leaders who has not gone
underground or into exile.
   He said Thursday that, though there are no more anti-government
street demonstrations and other protest has been quashed, ``The
crisis has deepened in that society simply refuses to function.''
   He said he believes Noriega realizes he cannot hold on
indefinitely.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
