<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Mecham 2ndLd-Writethru a0658 05-14 0938</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0658,0961</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mecham Criminal Trial Begins Thursday</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 7th graf ``Mecham, one'' to UPDATE with
Mecham and McCain reax to delegate selection. Picks up 8th graf pvs
``In the criminal.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Impeached former Gov. Evan Mecham, facing
trial this week on charges of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan,
proclaimed faith in his innocence but uncertainty about whether he
will be acquitted.
   Mecham remained in the spotlight Saturday, attending his state
party convention and narrowly winning a seat at the Republican
National Convention.
   Mecham, who was removed from office April 4 by the Legislature,
could be sentenced to up to 22 years in prison if found guilty on
all six felony counts of perjury, willful concealment and filing
false documents.
   His brother and 1986 campaign treasurer, Willard Mecham, will be
tried on three similar counts.
   The legal woes did not stop delegates to the state Republican
convention Saturday from picking Mecham to be one of the state's 33
delegates when the party convenes this summer in New Orleans.
   Mecham finished 17th in the balloting for 18 at-large delegates
after losing a bid for one of the delegate seats allocated by
congressional district.
   Mecham, one of the 717 delegates to his state party convention,
said before voting that he believed he had ``strong support'' from
rank-and-file party workers. Mecham supports Vice President George
Bush, but Bush campaign officials said Mecham was not on their list
of recommended delegates.
   Told the results by reporters, Mecham said ``Hurrah'' and thrust
his right fist upward. ``Well, for not being on a slate, that's not
too bad,'' he said, adding ``this was not a referendum on me.''
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., placed 10th in the at-large balloting
with 296 votes to Mecham's 271, and said he would attend the
convention despite earlier reluctance to serve in a delagation with
Mecham.
   ``Amazing,'' McCain said of the vote. ``I respect the decision
of the convention. I have no other comment about it.''
   In the criminal case, Mecham and his brother are accused of
concealing a $350,000 campaign loan from Tempe developer Barry
Wolfson by failing to report it on Evan Mecham's personal or
campaign financial statements.
   ``I have committed no crime,'' Mecham, 64, said in a telephone
interview last week. ``I should be found innocent because I don't
feel myself guilty as far as I can see.''
   However, Mecham shied away from predicting he will be exonerated
by a Maricopa County Superior Court jury and indicated he still may
be open to a plea agreement if it didn't involve pleading guilty to
a felony, a condition that prosecutors have rejected previously.
   Mecham's 15-month governorship was a stormy one, beginning with
his cancellation of a Martin Luther King holiday for state workers
and ending with his repeated claims that his political and legal
problems were the result of a massive conspiracy.
   He was removed from office when the Senate convicted him of
trying to thwart an investigation into an alleged death threat and
misusing $80,000 from a protocol fund by loaning it to his auto
dealership.
   The Senate dismissed a charge stemming from the campaign loan
after some senators argued that voting on it would prejudice
Mecham's criminal case.
   On Monday, attorneys were set to present oral arguments before
the state Court of Appeals on a defense request to throw out the
indictment. If they fail there, defense attorneys plan to go to the
state Supreme Court.
   If there is no delay, jury selection is scheduled to begin
Thursday.
   In insisting that he broke no laws, Mecham has advanced several
arguments:
   _ That the October 1986 loan was actually reported properly
because it was lumped with other funds and listed as a $465,000
loan from Mecham to his campaign. The funds were lumped together as
a ``time-saving matter,'' Mecham said.
   _ That the failure to report the loan was an ``honest mistake''
by Willard Mecham, who filled out the financial reports ``the best
he knew how.''
   _ That Mecham is the victim of selective prosecution because
other public officials have amended their reports without facing
criminal charges.
   _ That in any case, whether the loan was properly reported or
not, there was no criminal intent to hide it.
   The prosecution, however, is expected to point to a letter from
Mecham to Wolfson in which he promised the loan would ``remain
confidential.'' Another key piece of evidence is a November 1986
receipt that showed a $350,000 contribution to the campaign from
Mecham, although he acknowledged he made no such contribution.
   None of the attorneys involved _ prosecutors Barnett Lotstein
and Michael Cudahy, Mecham defense lawyer Michael Scott and
Willard's attorney, Joe Keilp _ is tipping his hand on trial
strategy.
   But among the witnesses expected to be called are a number of
key players inside and outside the Mecham administration, including
former top aide Donna Carlson. She was one of several co-signers of
the Wolfson loan and later was the object of the alleged death
threat that became the centerpiece of Mecham's Senate impeachment
conviction.
   The governor's successor, Democratic Gov. Rose Mofford, was
subpoenaed by the defense to testify about her knowledge of the
campaign finance reporting law. She herself is under investigation
for omissions from her reports, which she recently corrected.
   If the trial begins as scheduled, jury selection will start with
distribution of a questionnaire designed to ferret out people with
obvious bias.
   For his part, defense attorney Scott said, ``I'm confident that
he should be acquitted.'' But he added, ``I'm not confident that it
will happen.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
