<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MysteryWriters     05-14 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mystery Writers,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mystery Writers Auction Off Future Characters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prominent mystery writers Friday auctioned off
everything from character's names to dinner with a novelist who
just signed a $10 million contract.
   The auction at the New York Public Library raised more than
$2,100 for the Mystery Writers of America, which is holding its
annual conference here this week.
   The highest bid was $320 for dinner with Mary Higgins Clark, who
recently signed a $10.1 million deal with Simon & Schuster to write
four novels and a book of short stories.
   Clark, 60, of Saddle River, N.J., has published five mystery
novels, including the recent bestseller ``Weep No More My Lady,''
since receiving a $3,000 advance for her first one in 1976.
   One of the most heated bidding wars developed over the right to
have the bidder's name included in Donald E. Westlake's next novel
and to write a line of dialogue. Justin Scott, 40, of New York, won
with a bid of $260.
   Scott said he is a good friend of Westlake's and wants a little
good-natured revenge because the author visited him recently for a
weekend _ and spent the time working on the first chapter of his
next novel.
   ``I paid $260. He will pay blood,'' he said.
   Signed, limited editions of books also were sold, as were movie
posters and a collection of Sherlock Holmes memorabilia.
   Judith Norton, 27, of Bethpage, got one of the best deals,
bidding $25 to attend a June writer's workshop in Illinois. The
workshop and hotel lodging were estimated to be worth $175.
   She also will receive a free manuscript critique by author Sara
N. Paretsky.
   ``Now I have to figure a way to get to Evanston'' where the
hotel is situated, she said. ``I think it's invaluable to go
somewhere else and meet successful writers.''
</TEXT>
