<1ST_LINE>d f PM-OilPrices     05-14 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Edge Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices settled slightly higher to
end the week with another slow trading day.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for June delivery
of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. grade of crude oil,
closed Friday at $17.49 per 42-gallon barrel, up 1 cent from
Thursday's close.
   Among refined products for June delivery, contracts for
wholesale unleaded gasoline settled .42 cent higher at 52.34 cents
per gallon, while wholesale heating oil rose .24 cent to 47.47
cents per gallon.
   John Azarow, an analyst at the Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
securities firm, said the session amounted to ``a total non-event.''
   ``Volume was down,'' he said, mainly because of a lack of any
news able to move prices one way or the other.
   Also restricting volume, Azarow said, was a reluctance by some
traders to trade too heavily before the upcoming meeting of oil
ministers from the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries,
beginning June 8 in Vienna, Austria.
   At the meeting, the OPEC ministers are expected to try to find a
way to restrict production in order to drive prices higher.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
